	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Here are sections 5 and 6, 7 is rather long and I want to make sure it is decent before posting it.  Some of this is a bit on the raw side, but I'm sure I'll look back at it and cringe when I see my mistakes. <br />
<br />
May Tunare Bless Thee,<br />
Auroralee Borealis</i><br />
--------------------------------------------------------<br />
5<br />
****<br />
The ship captain was standing on the deck with an irritated look etched on his face when they returned.  Chrystal neither noticed nor cared when he mentioned he had schedule to keep.  Her head was swimming with thoughts, she had to get back to the Temple.  <br />
<br />
The ship made its way slowly on to Montorn.  Normally Chrystal would have wanted to spend some time in the beautiful castle made of crystal and white stone.  It was a place of great beauty and deep meditation.  She barely noticed the days that it took for them to finally dock in Flountance again.  The conversations she had with everyone were light but mostly she sat and meditated.  Orrin kept his distance but only so far, he did not want to see her become like him, and run away from her problems.  <br />
<br />
The evening before the ship was to return to Flountance, Chrystal stood on the deck watching the sunset over the water.  She had done this every evening hoping that the evening would tell her something new, alas once again it was just an evening with the stars starting to appear in the darkening sky.<br />
<br />
“Excuse me,” Godart asked from behind her clearing his throat.<br />
<br />
“Yes?”  She did not turn away from watching the sun.<br />
<br />
“I’ve been thinkin’” He stopped and shuffled his feet on the wooden deck.  “Ma’am, you are from the Temple right?”<br />
<br />
She gave him an affirmative nod, but still did not look at him.<br />
<br />
“Do you think I could go with you?”  <br />
<br />
She looked out at the setting sun.  Annoyed she turned and looked at the boy.  He was a typical cabin boy wearing short pants and a shirt, on his feet he wore thin sandals.  It was not unusual for boy like him to appear at the Temple wanting to help.  Most came as students, she even had taught a few students over the years.  “Do you know how to ride?”  She asked.<br />
<br />
He looked down at his sandals and wiggled his toes.  “I’ve never been on a ‘orse.”<br />
<br />
“I don’t have the time to teach you.” She turned back to look at the horizon.  Normally she would be more patient.<br />
<br />
“I’m a fast learner.”  He pleaded.<br />
<br />
“The speed that we have to go to return to the Temple will be hard on an experienced rider, and you are inexperienced.”  <br />
<br />
“I won’t complain.”<br />
<br />
Chrystal remained silent for a long time, Godart took several steps backward from her.  “I’ll get you a horse, but you will need to keep up.”<br />
<br />
“Really?  You will take me?”  Godart jumped up on the balls of his feet.  “I’ll go pack my things now.”  He took off in a run across the deck.<br />
<br />
Was this the sign she was looking for?  Chrystal shook her head slightly and wondered why Yamara seemed to hate her so.  She stood in her spot on the deck until the night was full of stars and the night winds blew cold sea air over her.  That was when she decided it was time to retire for the night the next day promised to be long.<br />
<br />
6<br />
****<br />
In Flountance the following morning they walked off the ship with Godart fast on their heels.  The captain of the ship saw this and called out after Godart, telling him how worthless he was.  The small group turned a blind eye to the angry captain and sought out a horse dealer.  Chrystal paid several gold pieces for three horses, the fastest the horse dealer boosted.  <br />
<br />
Mounting horses they took off at a fast clip in the direction of the Temple.  Even on horseback the Temple was a weeks travel from Flountance. When evening came they dismounted and rested.  Godart walked about on stiff legs but he want to admit that he was hurting for fear they would make him turn back.  Chrystal showed no sympathy as she normally would due to her hurried desire to get back to the Temple and fear she would never see it again.  <br />
<br />
Each day they rode through valleys and over rivers, creeks and mountains.  Only stopping at night to rest.  On the sixth day Chrystal relaxed a little, because they entered the Tolmarian Valley. <br />
<br />
They crested a small hill in the valley surrounded by tall majestic mountains.  "It is just up ahead!"  Chrystal announced putting her hand over her eyes to shade them from sun hoping to catch a glimpse of the Temple of Healers in the distance, but alas they were still too far.   <br />
<br />
"It is?"  Orrin questioned never having been in the Tolmarian valley himself this was new to him. <br />
<br />
Godart let out a small cheer.<br />
<br />
"Yes, come.  If we hurry we should make it to the Temple by nightfall.  And there are many to see."  Mainly the High Priest.  Yet, she had not been back for months and she was sure others would want a piece of her time as well. <br />
<br />
The horses carried them across the valley and by early evening they could see the statue of Yamara as she stood over the white temple.  Chrystal's heart leapt into her chest as they got closer to the temple.  "We are almost there!"  She exclaimed.  <br />
 <br />
"Aye milady, we are almost there." He smiled brightly at her. "This is the first time I have seen you this excited." <br />
<br />
"Come."  She felt as if she did not hurry she would never be able to enter the gates again. <br />
<br />
Godart dug his heels into the sides of his horse and they galloped off toward the Temple, but Orrin stopped his horse, Chrystal was about to do the same as Godart when she saw Orrin holding his beast back.<br />
<br />
"I'm sorry mi'lady, this is where we part.  I shall leave you here at the Temple where you belong and be on my way to where I belong." He told her solemnly as he turned his horse away from the temple.  He feared a long goodbye, because he did not want to leave her.  They had grown very close on their trek and he knew that it was best for them to quickly part. <br />
<br />
"What?"  She said grabbing the bridal of his horse as she gaped at him.  Thinking fast she closed her jaw with a snap.  "Well, uh, stay the night at least, I mean it is late and we could get you a room to stay in for the night as opposed to the ground."  She pleaded trying to come up with a real reason for him to stay. <br />
<br />
"I could sure use a soft warm place to lay my head for the night." He said trying to sound happy.     <br />
<br />
"And a good meal." <br />
<br />
"And a good meal, yes."  He confirmed. <br />
<br />
"Come," She said triumphantly letting go of the bridal and following Godart’s wake to the temple gates.  About halfway to the gate Godart was waiting for them, together again they slowed the horses and approached the gates.  At the gates the guards stepped up to meet them.   "Halt in the name of the Goddess of Life."  One of the two guards announced raising his hand to them.  In the other held a long spear. <br />
<br />
Chrystal dismounted and walked up to the guard.  "I am Priestess Chrystal daughter of Cornim." <br />
<br />
"Greetings Chrystal."  The second guard chirped happily. <br />
<br />
" Toonk!"  She returned, turning to face the young guard.  He wore the armor of a larger man, but his gaunt face under the helmet showed him as very thin.  "How have you been?" <br />
<br />
"Wonderful, it is great to see you again,” He nearly cheered, then he caught site of Orrin, “Who are your friends?" <br />
<br />
"This is Orrin of Donmar."  She said introducing Orrin.  “And this is Godart.” <br />
<br />
"Greetings Orrin of Donmar, then I guess you are not a Grot."  The first guard stated looking Orrin over from head to toe. <br />
<br />
"No."  Orrin answered. <br />
<br />
"We haven’t heard much about Donmar of late, are things well there?"  The first guard asked. <br />
<br />
"Donmar is a quiet place, well at least it was, but that is the business I have with the High Priest."  Orrin explained. <br />
<br />
“And Godart was it?”  The guard asked.<br />
<br />
The boy timidly nodded.<br />
<br />
“Pleasure to meet you.”<br />
<br />
"Perhaps we should let you three in so that you can tend to your business. "  Toonk responded quickly before the other guard could speak.    <br />
<br />
The other guard shot him a condescending look.  "I'm sure the High Priest Nonpree would like to see you right away."<br />
<br />
Toonk coward slightly but opened the gates. <br />
<br />
"Thank you,” Chrystal said pausing on her way in the gate.  “Toonk, perhaps later when you are off duty we can speak."  She said giving the young man a pleasant smile.   <br />
<br />
"I would like that very much.  I will be off by dinner, perhaps we can meet afterward at the usual spot?" <br />
<br />
"I will be there."  She promised not indicating where this spot might be.  They waved as the three of them continued through the gates.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Last edited by Auroralee on 08-28-2003 at 11:14 PM</i></font></p>
