	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Since I did sort of leave everyone at a high point I'll try to bring it down a little, this is turning out to be a longer story than I thought.  I'm wondering if this forum will be able to support the whole story or if I will need to just turn around and eventually offer to e-mail it to folks when I'm done.<br />
<br />
Yes, I said the story was done at one time, but really the story line is done I've been adding and arranging things as I go. <br />
<br />
May Tunare Bless Thee,<br />
<br />
Auroralee Borealis</i><br />
-----------------------------------------------------<br />
7<br />
****<br />
Orrin and Godart dismounted once through the gates to walk next to Chrystal, leading their horses.  She led the way to the stables where they left the horses and returned to the tall temple steps.  They ominously looked like the stairway to Goddess’s heaven.<br />
<br />
"What was that all about?"  Orrin asked as they climbed the steps of the inner temple, and Godart was further back out of listening distance.  His stiffness was preventing his movements.  <br />
<br />
"Toonk?"  She asked. <br />
<br />
"Yes." He said trying not to sound…  jealous.  <br />
<br />
"When I'm in the Temple I help him with his studies.  I am sure he has learned much in the time that I have been away this time.  He really has been a fine student."  Glancing over her shoulder she watched Godart struggle with the climb and chanted a few words to relieve his pains.<br />
<br />
"Ah,” He sighed inwardly, “But you don't spend much time here at the Temple." <br />
<br />
"True, I do spend a lot of time away, but I’m sure in light of the recent events I will stay here.  I know I am safe here."  The confidence of when he met her returned to her voice. <br />
<br />
Orrin looked down at her, "I must continue on to Donmar, to get my son, and even though this weighs heavily on your mind I still wish you would join me."   <br />
<br />
"I know."  She returned with a sigh.  They had discussed this several times and had not yet agreed on a decision.  "We shall discuss it later, but now we must go before the High Priest."  They were close to the top of the stairs and the fear of seeing Nonpree again almost out weighed the fear of the unknown evil.<br />
<br />
At the top of the stairs Chrystal pushed open the heavy doors and led the way in.  Inside a young priest in long white robes greeted them.  "Chrystal!"  He said happily, "You have returned to the Temple." <br />
<br />
With a large smile Chrystal hugged the young priest.  "Timpten, it is good to see you." Timpten only appeared young but was actually about twice Orrin’s age.  <br />
<br />
"How were your travels?  Did you talk with the Shridian witchdoctor?"  Timpten asked when they ended their embrace.  “Gingsam isn’t in the temple tonight if you are looking for him, but he’s been spending a lot of time in the library.”<br />
<br />
She halted a moment looking at the gold designs in the tiles on floor.<br />
<br />
“What is wrong?”  He said turning his head to the side to look at her.<br />
<br />
"I’m here to see Nonpree, because I never actually met with the witchdoctor." <br />
<br />
Timpten raised his chin and gave her a curious look and took a moment to search her face then he looked upon Orrin and Godart.  "He is meditating right now, might I tell him how urgent it is?" <br />
<br />
"An Oracle was forced from this realm." <br />
<br />
"Goodness to Yamara," Timpten's eye's grew wide when he realized the seriousness of her words.  "I shall go to him at once."  Then as an after thought he looked back at them, "Please follow me, I'll have you sit and wait." <br />
<br />
They followed him to a quiet chamber off the main hall where some comfortable chairs had been set around a low table.  It was a tearoom.  Timpten bade them to sit and wait as he left. <br />
<br />
"Are you well Chrystal?"  Orrin asked. <br />
<br />
Her face was paler than usual and she fidgeted with her hands.  "Nervous," She returned.  "The last time I talked to Nonpree was before I was a student here, and I was in trouble for a juvenile stunt I did."   <br />
<br />
Orrin laughed, "How long ago was that?" <br />
<br />
"About a century ago."  She returned.  "I’ve avoided him ever since." <br />
<br />
"It must have been some stunt." <br />
<br />
"It was."  She gave a meek smile and pushed a wisp of white hair nervously behind her ear.  The memory of her childish mistake still hung heavy in her mind, and she was sure he would remember the moment he saw her. <br />
<br />
They sat for a while in silence.  Orrin decided he would ask the High Priest Nonpree about the Oracle's vision of his son.  He had heard that the High Priest was capable of seeing the future, perhaps he would have the answer.   <br />
<br />
Without any preamble the door swung open and in walked the High Priest Nonpree.  He was a small man, not much taller than a dwarf.  He wore a long white beard that nearly reached his waist.  His long white hair was pulled back at the nape of his neck in a braid.   <br />
<br />
"Priestess Chrystal daughter of Cornim, good to see you again.  I imagine you are trying to stay out of trouble."  <br />
<br />
Chrystal stood and bowed before him. "If I am in trouble this time, it is trouble that has found me."  She said sitting back down. <br />
<br />
The High Priest gave a snort and turned his attention to Godart.  “And you are?”<br />
<br />
“Uh…” The boy stuttered popping to his feet.  <br />
<br />
“Trouble, eh?”  The High Priest laughed.<br />
<br />
“Godart, your lordlyship sir.”  The boy followed Chrystal’s lead and bowed deeply then sat back in his seat.<br />
<br />
Nonpree gave him a smile and turned to Orrin, "And who are you, Sir?"  <br />
<br />
Orrin remained seated but inclined his head as a true king.  "Orrin son of Onmil of Donmar."  <br />
<br />
Nonpree perked his head to this, as he found a comfortable chair to perch himself feet first on. "King of Donmar?" <br />
<br />
"I was." <br />
<br />
"You must tell me what happened."  Nonpree said keeping his attention on Orrin.   <br />
<br />
Orrin began to tell his story.  The story of how Norlin came to the kingdom while he was away and killed his entire family excepting he assumed the eldest prince after what the Oracle said.  He stated that Norlin currently held the lands of Donmar, and that he was on his way back to Donmar to retrieve the young prince from Norlin's clutches. <br />
<br />
In his perched position on the chair Nonpree templed his hands as he listened.  When it seemed that Orrin was done he leaned his head forward to rest his chin on his fingertips and closed his eyes.  He seemed to disappear into a deep meditation.  <br />
<br />
After a long silence he spoke again.  "Something tells me the two of you are linked.” He said waving a hand in the air directed toward Chrystal and Orrin.  “How did you meet?" <br />
<br />
"I healed him in Shridian caves."  Chrystal said cutting in for the first time. <br />
<br />
"And that’s what brought you together?" <br />
<br />
"By a strange twist of fate after that we were taken to the Southern plains near Fountance.  It was once we were in Fountance the Minno Oracle called to me, and that is why we are here."  She informed him.   <br />
<br />
Nonpree slowly nodded his head in acknowledgement of her statement indicating she say more. <br />
<br />
"The Oracle told us of Orrin's son, and that something looms over me, but before it explained more," She gulped some saliva into her dry throat.  "The Oracle disappeared." <br />
<br />
Godart sucked in his breath, everyone had nearly forgotten he was there.<br />
<br />
"Disappeared?"  Nonpree asked looking directly into her eyes.<br />
<br />
"It gave a terrible scream and then disappeared." <br />
<br />
"This is serious.  What have you done?"  <br />
<br />
"Nothing that I know of."  She squeaked. <br />
<br />
Nonpree closed his eyes and remained that way for a moment to reflect inwardly, and then he looked at her.  "There is something different about you."  He leaned forward to peer at her closer.  "You bear a mark Chrystal." <br />
<br />
"A mark?"  She paused for a moment remembering the Oracle’s words, "The Oracle mentioned a mark, but what mark?" <br />
<br />
"I don't know.  Give me three days for the High Council to convene."  <br />
<br />
"Anything you need."    <br />
<br />
 Nonpree turned to Orrin, "I would also like for you to remain.  Due to the link, I think it would be wise.  Plus, if Donmar has fallen into hands of a dark sorcerer this cannot be good.  The Council shall discuss this matter as well." <br />
<br />
Orrin and Chrystal exchanged glances.  “I will remain until after the Council meets.”     <br />
<br />
"Thank you, your Majesty."  Nonpree returned with a bow of his head.  "I'm sure Chrystal can arrange appropriate guest quarters for you." <br />
<br />
"Yes."  Chrystal whispered.   <br />
<br />
The High Priest leapt from his perch, "Good day and I will talk again with you soon."  He said then ambled to the door, but lingered before leaving.  “Godart.”  He said turning back.  “Come with me, I think you are wishing to take up residence in the Temple.”  The boy jumped from his chair and gave his two companions a worried glance.  Chrystal gave him a reassuring smile.  <br />
<br />
“Yes sir,” He said following the High Priest out of the room. <br />
<br />
Chrystal and Orrin took several moments to stare at one another in silence.  Fear was welling up inside her.  The whole Council was going to meet and talk about her. "Perhaps the Council can offer some explanation."  She said breaking the silence then added as an afterthought.  "They are not all healers." <br />
<br />
"So I have heard." <br />
<br />
She stood from her chair.  Her body quaked so hard that it felt as if her legs would give at any moment crashing her to the floor.  "Well,” She said steadying herself with a hand on the chair back, “I need to get you quarters."      <br />
<br />
"Everything will be fine."  He assured her standing and placing a hand on her shoulder.  He could feel her shake under his touch. <br />
<br />
"I’m sure it will."  She said looking down avoiding eye contact with him. <br />
<br />
"I'll be here for you." <br />
<br />
"I…” She stumbled over her words a moment, “I don't want to mention this to anyone," She tried concentrating on the intricate design and lively colors in the woven carpet on the floor.  "Even though by morning the whole Temple will know.  Words of bad news spread fast." <br />
<br />
"They usually do.”  Orrin nodded.<br />
<br />
She raised her head a little and looked at his hand on her shoulder.  “I think for the sake of others that you should not touch me again while we are here." <br />
<br />
Orrin removed his hand from her shoulder and looked at the offending limb with a frown, "I can do that."  He kept forgetting she was not a typical woman but that she was a Priestess of Yamara, with all the vows there of. <br />
<br />
With a solemn nod, Chrystal led the way out of the inner Temple to the courtyard again and turned to the left taking them to a large stone building.  Pushing open the door she saw others whom she knew.  These were the temple students and residence.  She greeted them with a painted smile telling them how wonderful it was to be home.  <br />
<br />
Leaving them she led them further down a hall until they came upon a small round woman, who greeted her in the melodic tones of Tolmarian.  This was an old friend whom everyone called Ma Dean.  She was the head caretaker for the main residence.  <br />
<br />
“Ma,” Chrystal returned in the same melodic Tolmarian tongue.  “Nonpree would like for you to find his Majesty Orrin of Donmar a place to sleep.  He will be our guest for a few days.”<br />
<br />
Ma Dean sized him up for a moment.  “Where is his entourage?”<br />
<br />
“He is alone.”<br />
<br />
“How odd.”  Ma Dean returned shaking her head.  “No bother, I think I have just the place for him.  Follow me.”  She said leading the way.  They went up a winding staircase and then into a long hall.  Doors lined either side and after passing several doors she stopped before a big door about midway down the hall.   <br />
<br />
"Here we are."  Ma Dean said in the common language as she opened a door.  "I hope it is to your liking your majesty."  She gave a palm out gesture toward the room as she nodded to Orrin. <br />
<br />
"This is better than I could have asked for.  Thank you."  Orrin told her with a bow. <br />
<br />
"I shall make sure clothes and water are brought up so you can clean up and change before sup. " <br />
<br />
"Thank you again ma’am."  He gave Ma Dean a smile and she disappeared leaving him and Chrystal to stand partially in the sleeping chamber and partially out.  "Well shall we?"  He said indicating to the room. <br />
<br />
"I'm going to go to my quarters, please make yourself comfortable."  Chrystal gave him a smile and bowed her head. <br />
<br />
"Alright then I shall see you at supper?" <br />
<br />
She thought a moment, "Yes." <br />
<br />
“Oh a quick question.”  Perhaps he could delay her from leaving.<br />
<br />
“Yes?”<br />
<br />
“Does everyone speak, your language here?”<br />
<br />
Chrystal shook her head, “Only a few speak Tolmarian.  It is a dying tongue and those of us that speak it try to speak it first.  I will try to remember to keep my language in a tongue you understand.”<br />
<br />
“It is fine, I was just wondering if I needed to learn Tolmarian.”<br />
<br />
"Perhaps someday.”  She returned with a smile.  “I shall see you at Supper."  She then turned and disappeared down the hall.  <br />
<br />
He stepped into the room and slowly closed the door.  He was alone again.  It was not exactly what he wanted.  He really wished she had stayed to talk to him, even if it meant teaching him her language.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
	</td></tr></table>
