	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-01-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">02:52 AM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Okay now I have to live up to the thoughts of not letting you guys down /smile.  I was able to put more work into it this weekend.  My portable computer just broke on me making it a bit more difficult for me to type my thoughts where ever I please.  I had to put a notebook in my purse.  <br />
<br />
I have some Real Life things coming up this week so I may not get the chance to add anymore to the story for a while.  I hope you enjoy, these next 2 sections.<br />
<br />
May Tunare Bless Thee,<br />
<br />
Auroralee Borealis</i><br />
--------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
8<br />
****<br />
<br />
Chrystal arrived after Orrin was cleaned and dressed in a borrowed outfit of dark blue velvet.  She wore a plain dark red dress that flowed to the floor.  He was pleased to see her dressed like a lady.  Her white hair was wound up and pinned behind her head.  <br />
<br />
“You look nice.”  He told her with a gasp when he opened the door.  <br />
<br />
“Thank you.”  She bowed her head and looked at her hem.  They did not exchange much conversation as she led him to the dinning hall.  They stepped into the great room, which was filled with several long tables covered with food.  <br />
<br />
After the meal Chrystal disappeared, he was certain she was off talking to the guard from the gate. <br />
<br />
He decided to find his way back to his room. <br />
<br />
“Your majesty,” A voice asked him as he exited the dinning hall.<br />
<br />
He turned to see Godart walking up to him and bowing.  “Can I walk with you?”<br />
<br />
“Yes.”  He turned back in the direction of his quarters with Godart in tow.<br />
<br />
“I’s listening to your story ‘bout your Kingdom and your son.  ‘Ow ol’ is he?”<br />
<br />
Orrin turned and looked at the boy.  He had grown rather fond of Godart during their travel, in many ways he reminded him of his son Onjovn.  “He’s about your age Godart, a strong young man.”<br />
<br />
“Think I’ll ever get to meet ‘im?”<br />
<br />
“That would be nice.”<br />
<br />
“I’d like it very much.”  He stopped talking for a moment and looked up at Orrin’s face.  “I wanna ‘elp you save ‘im.”<br />
<br />
Orrin sucked in his breath, this boy no older than his son wanted to save his son?  It was noble of him, but even boys get killed.  “I don’t think it is a safe idea.  You should probably stay here so you can grow to be a man, then you would make a noble knight.”<br />
<br />
“You really think so?”  Godart said with a flash of excitement in his eyes.  “You mean me a knight?  Like the Capt’n O’ the Guard.”<br />
<br />
Orrin nodded, “But first you need to become a man.  You are no good to anyone as a dead boy.”<br />
<br />
Godart looked away a briefly, “I’m not a boy your majesty.”  <br />
<br />
“You are at the edge of manhood.  It is a very trying stage and this is where you will learn what you will be.”  He took a moment to think of what Onjovn was going through.  Norlin was surely trying to use this stage in his life to change him, to twist his beliefs and to turn him.<br />
<br />
“Your majesty?”<br />
<br />
“Yes.”<br />
<br />
“Thank you for believin' in me, no one ever ‘as.”<br />
<br />
“Now, young man,” He decided it was better than calling him boy, “You should probably return to your room and get rested.  I’m sure they will have learning for you in the morning.”<br />
<br />
“Oh, that they do sire.  ‘Is Lordlyship ‘igh Priest said I will begin studies right away.  ‘E was really nice to me.”<br />
<br />
Orrin gave the boy, no young man, a pat on his back and Godart ran off across the courtyard.  Turning back to his original mission Orrin found his way back to his sleeping quarters and prepared for bed.  He left the bed curtains open and lay watching the canopy above the bed as the starter lamp’s flame made shadows dance on it.<br />
<br />
He leapt out of bed when someone tapped lightly on the door.  If it was Chrystal he did not want to risk missing her.  "Chrystal, come in."  He had to control his excitement at seeing her.   <br />
<br />
"Uh, did I wake you?"   She said looking at his attire, he was only in a dressing shirt.<br />
<br />
"No, I was only preparing. I hadn't actually fallen asleep yet."  He fibbed, he was already in a dreamy state when she knocked. <br />
<br />
She smiled and entered the dark room, it was obvious he had been sleeping.  "I should go if you are prepared for sleep.”  She said pursing her lips and peering into the darkness.<br />
<br />
"Oh, hold on let me get a lamp."  He disappeared into the gloom and reappeared with the starter lamp and lit a couple oil lamps.  This brightened the room a bit more.  <br />
<br />
Now she could see him better in his dressing gown, it only came to the top of his knees showing his hairy legs down to his bare feet.  The thought of his naked legs made her flush.  "I wanted to come by and ask how you were doing.”  She said regaining her composure, “I fear I’m not being a very good host.  Here you are in my home and what have I done since I’ve been here?  I've run off on you." <br />
<br />
He smiled at her.  "Please sit."  He said indicating to one of the chairs. <br />
<br />
"I really should go to my own bed now." <br />
<br />
"I would like to talk with you a moment."  She took his strong hint and sat.  He sat in another chair near her.  "I wanted to tell you that I'm glad we are here."  There was an awkward moment as he chose his words.  There was so much more he wanted to tell her but kept realizing exactly how inappropriate it was.  "Also,”  He plodded on, breaking the silence again, “That as soon as the Council meets I must be on my way." <br />
<br />
"I know, and as much as I would want to join you, I am sure the council will see it fit I stay here.  Whatever took the Oracle will be less likely to come here, because of the strength of the Temple.  Otherwise I would join you." <br />
<br />
"You would?"  He asked with a slight crack to his voice. <br />
<br />
"Yes, what you have to do is not going to be easy.  I think Nonpree realizes it and that is why he wants you to stay until after the Council meets.  I'm sure they will send a Priest with you.  You will need a strong healer by your side.  I don't know if I could even help if it came down to it." <br />
<br />
"I would never doubt you.  I know you would never fail me."   <br />
<br />
A smile slipped across her face as she looked down at her hands in her lap.  "You are overly kind." <br />
<br />
"Will I get the opportunity to talk with you tomorrow?" <br />
<br />
"Yes."  She returned, "I won't find so many things to do tomorrow.  Plus you are my guest and it will be my responsibility to show you around." <br />
<br />
"Alright then."  Orrin said standing with a stretch and a yawn.  "I shall see you in the morning." <br />
<br />
Chrystal stood as well and for a moment they only stood looking at one another.  "Yes, in the morning."  She announced breaking the air of silence. <br />
<br />
9<br />
****<br />
<br />
The following day they spent together with Chrystal showing Orrin the Temple grounds. This in many ways made him homesick but he was still happy to be here with her.  They walked many of the gardens and through the various buildings. By afternoon she took Him to the library of the Temple.  An enormous room with books higher than the eye could see.  There were others in the library studying but none took notice of them.   <br />
<br />
In the corner of the room seated in a chair was a scholarly fellow that wore long robes of station.  His long light brown hair was tied back in a ponytail though he probably was much older than the color made him look.  On his youthful face he wore no mustache but had a small beard on his chin.  He was a caster of some sort and Chrystal dragged Orrin straight to him.  "Gingsam," She whispered. <br />
<br />
Closing his book he looked up at her, removing a pair of spectacles and putting them into a pocket.  "Chrystal, it is good to see you again."  She smiled at him.  He was one of her oldest friends.  "Come with me I want to show you something."  He said as he put the book on a table next to his chair and standing.  He apparently wanted to show her some new magic he had learned.   It was forbidden to practice inside the library so they had to go elsewhere.  The fear was that a spell would be cast wrong and burn up the whole library.   <br />
<br />
Gingsam led the way outside onto a balcony.  “Just stand there.”  He told her as he put his hands together and chanted a few words then he opened his palms.  In them sat butterflies of vibrant colors.  Once released they flew around Chrystal and landed in her white hair.  "What do you think?"  He said with a toothy smile. <br />
<br />
She giggled as a young girl would.  "They are beautiful." <br />
<br />
“Nothing compared to you my dear.”<br />
<br />
"You are not a priest."  Orrin observed. <br />
<br />
"No, I am Gingsam of Vnalt.  I am a magician." <br />
<br />
"I'm sorry for not offering proper introductions," She said realizing her mistake.  "Orrin of Donmar, well um, you already introduced yourself Gingsam.  He is a member of the High Council." <br />
<br />
"Oh?  Well, it is a pleasure to meet you Gingsam of Vnalt."  Orrin told him with a bow.  <br />
<br />
"As it is a pleasure to finally meet you your Majesty."  Gingsam said returning the bow.  "I hear the two of you are in some type of trouble." <br />
<br />
"I don't know exactly what type yet."  She told him.  "All I know is that I bear some type of mark and that something looms over me." <br />
<br />
"Interesting."  He said as he cast a long pipe, which he placed between his lips.  "Nonpree eluded to something last night when I spoke with him.  Apparently you have him concerned since he called the whole Council together.  I will try what I can.  I don't know what this mark is that you bear but there is a certain aura about you.  It is a pleasant aura.  I will read up on it tonight." <br />
<br />
"Now you are scaring me."  She replied. <br />
<br />
"Oh it is nothing to be frightened of dear."  Gingsam told her kindly as he sucked in deeply on his pipe and let the smoke pass back out of his lips.  "And you Orrin, I hear there is a sad story about Donmar." <br />
<br />
"Aye, that there is."  Orrin replied and began to tell the magician the tale he had told Nonpree.   <br />
<br />
When Orrin was done Gingsam stood quietly sucking on his pipe.  "Well your two stories would be enough to pull the whole Council in.  I hope the prince is still in good health."   <br />
<br />
"As do I."  Orrin returned.  "He is my last hope." <br />
<br />
"Losing so much can cause ones outlook to drop.  But do tell me how did you happen to be in the caves of the Shridian?" <br />
<br />
Orrin thought to himself a moment, "I don't know I just knew I needed to go there.  It was like a calling." <br />
<br />
"Now this does get interesting.  Chrystal was at the caves to see the witchdoctor.  Did you ever see him?" <br />
<br />
"No, I'm sorry Gingsam."  <br />
<br />
"It's all right I will return there myself sometime.  It's waited this many years I'm sure the old boy will live for many more so I can eventually ask him myself." <br />
<br />
This piqued Orrin's curiosity.  "You mean you asked her to go there?" <br />
<br />
"Yes and no, I mentioned it and Chrystal volunteered to go."  Gingsam told him. <br />
<br />
"It sounded like an adventure." <br />
<br />
"And so it turned into one."  Orrin said with a smile. <br />
<br />
"That it sounds like," Gingsam returned.  "But I don't think the adventure is over for either of you."</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Last edited by Auroralee on 09-01-2003 at 03:34 AM</i></font></p>
