	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-03-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">06:45 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><i>I do worry I might have rushed these next two parts to the story.  I hope they make sense, I'll probably be back later to look them over and realize my billion and one mistakes.<br />
<br />
I've started back to college and I seem to try to ignore my World Civilization homework. /giggle.<br />
<br />
May Tunare Bless Thee,<br />
<br />
Auroralee Borealis</i><br />
<br />
10<br />
****<br />
The days passed and each day more of the High Council arrived with great fanfare.  Finally on the third day as promised the Council met.  It was late evening and after the supper meal when Timpten led Chrystal and Orrin into the Council chamber.  It was a large circular room that contained twenty-one seats that sat in a circle.  Chrystal and Orrin stood in the middle of this circle feeling like criminals preparing for the verdict and sentencing for their crimes.<br />
<br />
"Welcome."  Nonpree told them.  Even his words did not take the tense edge off the situation.  He stopped for a long time seeming to collect his thoughts.  "As you are aware we have met to discuss the situation that surrounds the two of you.  It is of great concern that your adventures have so far involved the disappearance of the Minno Oracle.  Also that on the throne of Donmar sits a wizard who commands a Dragon.  Still shrouded in mystery is the link between the two of you, but in time we are certain that will reveal itself.  <br />
<br />
“To save the Grandson of Onmil and future king of Donmar, it is imperative that his Majesty Orrin of Donmar return to his proper place.  It is foreseen that the battle will not be an easy task, and each member will return to their homes and send what is willing of their people to assist with this battle.  From the Temple of Yamara I will send with you Chrystal daughter of Cornim as your healer and a priestess of Yamara.  She is better at her skills than she believes.”  Nonpree said looking upon her face, she dared not protest nor turn away from his stare.<br />
<br />
“Chrystal Priestess of Yamara and daughter of Cornim.”  He formally addressed her.  “It was also decided that you remain away from the Temple until your pursuer is discovered.  It is the belief of this council that it would jeopardize the lives of all in the Temple if you remain.”  <br />
<br />
Her jaw slackened.  Say it isn’t so!  She wanted to scream out.  She snapped her jaw shut realizing he meant what he said, she was banished.<br />
<br />
"You may both stay the night.  The first morning light your horses will be ready to take you to Donmar.”  He turned back to Orrin.  “This Council owes you an apology for wasting much of your time Orrin, and we hope you will forgive us."  <br />
<br />
“Chrystal it is not our intention to leave you defenseless in the wilderness.”  He waved his hand and Timpten stepped forward holding three items on outstretched arms, which were draped with a cloak.  The items where a shield, and across it lay a sheathed sword with gems inlaid at its hilt aside a white metallic scepter.  "Please take the Scepter of Life with you, it shall aid you in your task.  It can bring back recently departed souls, a skill you already know how to use, but this will make it easier.  It is also able to ward off enemies with the wrath of Yamara."<br />
<br />
Chrystal lifted the white scepter from the shield.  She had been told about the scepter and it was one of the most valued items of Yamara, and now they were entrusting her with it.  She turned it in her hand it was lighter than it appeared and radiated a cool aura.  <br />
<br />
Timpten then sidestepped to stand in front of Orrin.  "Your majesty” Nonpree addressed him.  “Please accept these tokens of our good faith.  The Sword of Trinity, and the Shield of Healing.  The sword cuts through magics, and the shield if laid across a small injury will heal that injury."  Orrin picked up the armament, both items were lighter than they appeared.  <br />
<br />
Timpten bowed and turned back to Chrystal again.  He wrapped the cloak around her shoulders.  “Wear this for your warmth and safety.”  He told her softly.  Then he stepped out of the circle.   <br />
<br />
Nonpree bowed his head in prayer.  "May the Goddess of Life Yamara guide you on your path and smile down upon you.” <br />
<br />
"I will accompany them."  Gingsam said aloud. <br />
<br />
"You Gingsam?"  Nonpree was surprised at this. <br />
<br />
"They will need the help of a mage to go against this wizard Norlin.  Especially if you intend for his Majesty to get close enough to actually use that sword."   <br />
<br />
"Very well.”  Nonpree said with a bow of his head.  “After a long day we shall adjourn.”  <br />
<br />
Chrystal and Orrin bowed deeply at the waist before the Council and left the chamber.  They remained silent as they left the temple.  Orrin walked by her side to her room where she opened the door.  She walked into the room without a word to him and closed the door.<br />
<br />
This was too much for her.  She held the scepter tightly in her hand not realizing her knuckles were white.  Once the door was closed she collapsed to the floor.  She did not like the idea of being cast out, yet she understood that she could not endanger the temple.  These were Yamara’s wishes.  On her knees she prayed to the Goddess, wishing that the Goddess would speak to her and let her know why.<br />
 <br />
11<br />
****<br />
<br />
During the night the members of the council sent their fastest runners toward their homes.  There was not much time to waste Orrin was going to need to organize an army on the move.  <br />
<br />
It was early morning when they met Nonpree in front of the inner Temple.  Their horses and packs had been prepared for them.  He bowed before Chrystal as she mounted her horse the one she had brought from Flountance.  “Be careful Chrystal there is much that is unknown.”<br />
<br />
“I shall try.”<br />
<br />
Gingsam also mounted his horse a dappled gray, “His Majesty and I will be with her she’ll be safe.”  He said giving Chrystal a wink.<br />
<br />
Everyone turned their heads when a door across the courtyard banged open and out popped Godart.  “You can’t leave without me!”  He said running breathlessly to them.<br />
<br />
Nonpree clapped his hands, “Prepare the boy a horse as well, he came with them perhaps it is his destiny to go to Donmar with them.”  No one protested this proclamation.  <br />
<br />
Godart was given a horse and a pack, and soon Nonpree was waving goodbye as they exited the gates of Yamara’s Temple.<br />
<br />
The days passed and the horses carried them at an easy pace east toward Donmar.  Orrin had to hold back from pushing the animal.  He needed to make sure his timing was correct and to allow reinforcements to join them.  If Norlin were to take him and his small party of the four of them by surprise they would surely be dead. <br />
 <br />
He kept having dreams of seeing his dear son Onjovn again.  In his sleep he would hold the boy in his arms and cry into his blond hair.  In his waking he tried to focus on the task they had ahead.  He really did not know how to face a dragon and he was not even sure if he would have the men to fight in the name of Donmar.  Was there anything left of his army?  Were his captains smart enough to have the men retreat from the castle?  He now admonished himself for running away.  It was not how a king was supposed to act.  If he were a good king he would have fought back immediately to regain his crown.  <br />
<br />
Trying to shake his thoughts from the idea he did wrong he realized that without proper planning and in his grief he would have died and Norlin would have won.  This way there was still a chance.  The Gods and seen to it.  That was why he ran, and why he found Chrystal.  <br />
<br />
Looking upon Chrystal now, she had sobered from the day they had met.  She was now quieter but she did not seem as shy as she held her head high.  Her quiet demeanor bothered him.  When she did talk she kept it to the mission ahead and did not want to speak about the fact that she was being outcast for an evil mark.  He could not stand that she was troubled and knew it was up to him to do something.  Here she had willingly helped him without asking anything in return.   <br />
<br />
He let his horse fall back and he walked it along side hers because the path was wide enough.  “You never did tell me what it was you did that Nonpree would remember.”  He asked trying to open a thread of communication.<br />
<br />
She looked at him and blinked with her dark eyes, even her eyelashes were dark, which was a contrast from her pure white hair.  “It was just a silly childish thing.  And not something I have ever lived down.”<br />
<br />
“Did you set fire to the library?”  He asked her.<br />
<br />
“No,” She giggled, “I am thankfully not the reason for the no casting in the library rule, because of that rule there hasn’t ever been a fire in the library.”<br />
<br />
“Did you turn a council member into a toad?”  <br />
<br />
“Oh goodness no.”<br />
<br />
“Then if it wasn’t any of those things what was it?”<br />
<br />
“You are trying to trap me sir.”  She said with the first real smile she had had since leaving for Minno island. <br />
<br />
He was pleased to see that she was smiling and hoped he could keep her happy, but kept a note in his mind to ask Gingsam later.  If it was so spectacular he was certain the rest of the council knew.<br />
<br />
Godart seeing an opportunity to talk with them drove his horse up between them.  “’Ello,” He said with a grin.  “I ‘ope you know I can wield a sword your majesty.”  <br />
<br />
“Let us hope you will not need to.”  Chrystal told him.  “There will be much need for your assistance.  Wars always need people to help them from behind the fighting lines.”<br />
<br />
“She has a point.”  Orrin returned trying not to show his annoyance with the boy’s intrusion.  There had to be a reason the Gods blessed them with him.<br />
<br />
“Will I be able to see the dragon?”<br />
<br />
“Most likely.”<br />
<br />
“I’ve never seen a real live dragon!”<br />
<br />
Chrystal nudged her horse in the ribs to get him to trot forward to Gingsam.  This abandoned Orrin with Godart.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
