	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-06-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">08:00 AM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">12<br />
****<br />
<br />
On the forth day, Orrin declared that they had entered the lands of Donmar.  It was fall in the highlands and the trees had started to color, the change would not reach the lowlands for a few weeks.  The smell of snow was in the air with the promise for an early winter.   <br />
<br />
They made it to Donmar before any other troops had been able to catch up to them.  Orrin was beginning to wonder if others would be on their way, and the early winter may make the passage of others into Donmar more difficult.<br />
<br />
Near mid-afternoon they arrived at a small shack on a hillside made of logs that over looked a deep valley.  Orrin explained that it was the home of an old widow that had worked in the castle when he was a boy.  They stopped their horses, Orrin dismounted and walked up to the door and knocked.  Shortly the door opened and in the doorway stood a woman that did not seem as old as Orrin had first described.  She was a tall slender woman wearing a floor length dress of simple brown.  A shawl was wrapped around her shoulders, and unbound black hair.  The hair was streaked with white from age now, but it was the only sign that she was aged at all. <br />
<br />
"Hello Madam Thinopen." He told her with a friendly smile. <br />
<br />
The woman's eyes widened, "Your majesty?" <br />
<br />
“Yes.”<br />
<br />
The woman dropped to her knee and lowered her head.  “Your Majesty!”<br />
<br />
"Please rise." He told her. <br />
<br />
When she rose, she looked at him.  "Sire, I thought you were dead." <br />
<br />
“No wizard is going to get the best of me.”  He retorted.<br />
<br />
For a brief moment a look of distain flashed across her face, “Ah yes, young Orrin you always were a fighter.  Come in for a bit we have much to discuss your majesty.”  She said inviting him in to her home.  Orrin looked over his shoulder at Gingsam, Godart and Chrystal.  She looked past Orrin at them as well.  “I see you have company.  Why don’t you bring them in for a bit of sup.”  <br />
<br />
"That would be wonderful." He waved to the other three to dismount and join him.   <br />
<br />
Godart did not hesitate to jump off of his horse and run to Orrin’s side.  Chrystal shared a quick glance with Gingsam, he seemed to have an uneasy feeling about this woman.  They dismounted and removed the bridals and saddles from the horses.  Once free the four horses set off to find a patch of yellowing grass. <br />
<br />
Moments later the group of four sat around a rough wooden table as Thinopen busied herself at a pot over the fire.  The smell of cooking food and wood smoke filled the small one room cottage, which seemed like a cave.  The only illuminations were from the fire in the stone fireplace and a small window on the wall near the door that caught the light of the sun’s rays.   <br />
<br />
Gathering her shawl around her, Thinopen used a large wooden spoon to stir something in the big black pot over the flames, "I foresaw visitors today," She explained, "So I started a stew.” <br />
<br />
 "You were always good at predicting future events.”  Orrin told her with a pleasant smile. <br />
<br />
She bowed her head, “If only I had been at the castle the day Norlin came.”  She remained quiet for a moment then turned around to look again at her visitor, "Now, would you please introduce me to you company sire?" She said letting her gaze fall upon Chrystal. <br />
<br />
"Of course," He said shocked that he had forgotten to do so earlier.  "This is Gingsam of Vnalt." He said pointing a hand toward the Magician.  “This is Godart, and...”  Stopped to watch Thinopen.<br />
<br />
The woman barely took notice of him as she stepped up to Chrystal taking her hand.  "And who are you my dear?" She asked not waiting for Orrin's introduction. <br />
<br />
"I'm Chrystal Priestess of Yamara." Chrystal returned, looking at the woman as she held her hand. <br />
<br />
"Oh a priestess." She said excitedly. "I can't say I have seen one with hair as white as yours.  It is as lovely as fresh fallen snow.  Perhaps I might even have a lovely comb to give you." <br />
<br />
"Thank you but that won't be necessary." Chrystal returned. <br />
<br />
"Anyway," Orrin said trying to finish the introductions.  "This is Madam Thinopen, she was the castle seer when I was a child."  <br />
<br />
"Have you ever married?" Thinopen asked Chrystal ignoring Orrin. <br />
<br />
"I am a priestess we never marry." <br />
<br />
"Ah, so you have never bore children." <br />
<br />
"No." Chrystal said dropping her brow.<br />
<br />
"Madam have you heard any news from the castle?" Orrin asked. <br />
<br />
She turned her attention from Chrystal long enough to glance at Orrin. "I have." <br />
<br />
"Is my son there?" <br />
<br />
"I have heard news of the prince." <br />
<br />
"Is he well?" <br />
<br />
"The prince is well, at this time.  I really don't know what Norlin is going to do with a child.  However I do hear news that Norlin will marry soon." She returned to her pot and stirred it again, then she pulled spoon out blew on it and licked a taste from it.  "Ahh, just right.  Please, get yourselves bowls and have some of the stew."  <br />
<br />
Each went to the pot, ladled stew into a bowl, and returned to the table to sit.  Thinopen seated herself across from Chrystal and watched her intently with dark raven eyes. <br />
<br />
"You said Norlin will marry soon?" Orrin asked.   <br />
<br />
"Yes, but no one knows who.  He is apparently keeping it for a surprise." <br />
<br />
"And what of the dragon?" <br />
<br />
"Ictom?” The dragon’s name rolled off her tongue easily.  “He remains by Norlin's side.  That is as long as he wears the ring of Dagnim otherwise known as the Dragon Keeper.  The ring makes his and the dragon’s thoughts the same.  It was created by the wizard Dagnim, but he has long since left this world."  <br />
<br />
"I did not know how he had come by the dragon.”<br />
<br />
"It was a rather ingenious really." She began to explain.  "Norlin discovered that it was actually a drunken fool that had the ring in his keep and was unaware of its power.  But he could not steal the ring it has to be given or...  Well the other was not possible, because Norlin was not a relative of such a fool.  Dagnim’s ring was made to be passed down through a bloodline.  <br />
<br />
“Knowing this he needed to have the man give him the ring.  So he challenged him to a game of chance.  For three weeks they played.  Each time the man would present some new trinket to bargain with.  Sometimes Norlin would let the man win, because he was always in full control and others he would win.  Finally, Norlin challenged him, while he was in a drunken stupor, to put the ring up for chance.  This being the item he most coveted he merely won the game, because he was always in charge of the game.  Before the man even knew what had happened Norlin and the ring were gone. <br />
"If you ask me the ring is wasted on a commoner." <br />
<br />
"It is better to waste it on a commoner then to let a wizard like Norlin have it." Orrin hissed. <br />
<br />
Gingsam pursed his lips, "Might I ask you good woman.  How you came to have this extensive knowledge?" <br />
<br />
"He is proud of his story and has told many,” She looked upon Gingsam with contempt. “I am but one set of ears that has traveled the halls of Donmar castle since the king left.  Norlin is not as bad as many seem to think he is, and he has even been kind enough to invite people to the castle.  Besides who is going to stand up to Ictom?  I don't imagine the four of you intend to." She told them with a voice that seemed to tear into the soul.  “It would take an army and even then Ictom is a dragon.”<br />
<br />
"If it means to get my son back.  I will face anything." Orrin told her boldly. <br />
<br />
"Orrin, don't be a fool," She hissed looking directly at him.  "There is no way to get the prince back.  Norlin is now the one with the heir to the throne." <br />
<br />
"My son you mean, he is the true heir to the throne, and Norlin can not make a claim that he is the boy's father, because I'm his father!"  Orrin’s voice raised a few decibels. <br />
<br />
"In the absence of the boy’s father he can claim to be the guardian of the boy.  Also, there is the likelihood that when he marries he will have children of his own.  At that point being established on the throne he can make your prince have an accident and his heir would then be next in line for the throne." <br />
<br />
“I hadn’t thought of that even.”  Orrin gasped, “This is worse than I realized.  He's only holding my son until he can make a formal claim on the throne.  We are running out of time." <br />
<br />
"We will not let it happen Orrin." Gingsam responded he was hesitant to add how, but knew that Orrin needed reassurance.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
As the two men spoke the woman slipped next to Chrystal and peered at her up and down.  "You are the daughter of a king are you not?" <br />
<br />
"Excuse me?" <br />
<br />
"Your father was a king." <br />
<br />
"No my father was a simple magician, much like Gingsam but not as knowledgeable in the craft." <br />
<br />
"You are not of noble blood?" <br />
<br />
"No." At this point the two men stopped talking to turn and listen to the two women.  "Why do you want to know so much of me?" <br />
<br />
"I like to know people." <br />
<br />
"There is not much to know." This was indeed strange since she had barely paid Gingsam or Godart a passing glance.  "I am a simple Priestess that heals the sick and injured..." <br />
<br />
"How old are you?" She persisted. <br />
<br />
"Does my age matter?" <br />
<br />
"Yes." <br />
<br />
"I'm over a century and under my second century.  As to what the real age is I don't know." <br />
<br />
"One-hundred forty-two years." <br />
<br />
"I believe so.  How did you guess?" <br />
<br />
"It says so in your eyes." <br />
<br />
"Does it?”  Hope suddenly filled her, “If you can read that, then perhaps you could explain a mark to me."  <br />
<br />
"Where is this mark you bear?" <br />
<br />
"That is the thing, I don't know." <br />
<br />
"It is an aura." Gingsam returned, "I was unable to find anything in my reading about it." <br />
<br />
The woman reached out her hands and touched Chrystal's face using her fingers to run over every feature, finally placing a thumb on Chrystal's lips and then letting it drop.  "I don't know, it is not anything I have ever seen before." <br />
<br />
"I have been told it is the mark of something evil, but no one seems to sense that the mark itself is the evil." <br />
<br />
"It is not evil.  It actually is a caressing aura that of someone touched by a love stronger than the bonds of this world.  If only I could feel that sort of love." <br />
<br />
She glanced at Gingsam then at Orrin, "I love no one other than life." She told the woman after several moments of thought.<br />
<br />
"Ah but everyone you have given life to loves you.  And there are others."  <br />
<br />
Chrystal's thoughts returned to the Grot she recently returned breath to.  Could he have inadvertently caused this?  Or could this mark be older than him?  Perhaps it was with the first man she helped.  "There are so many, how will I ever know who it is?" <br />
<br />
"There is no way to know." She said searching Chrystal's face.  "But I don't think you have as much to worry about as the Council believed.  Help Orrin save the heir to the kingdom.  In time you will be able to stand up to your fears and be a great leader." <br />
<br />
"I have no intent to be a leader.  I just want to be able to return home." <br />
<br />
"In the end you will." She told Chrystal confidently.   <br />
<br />
"I hope so."  Chrystal gave her a peculiar look.  What could this woman see? More so what was she not telling?<br />
<br />
"I thank you for your hospitality, but it is getting late and I would like to make the valley by sundown." Orrin said standing and stretching. <br />
<br />
"But your majesty it is already sundown." She said pointing toward the one small window.  "Please stay here tonight.  I have enough quilts for all of you, and the fire is warm." <br />
<br />
"If you insist Madam, we will, but we shall not burden you any farther." <br />
<br />
"It is no bother, also there is more stew and I have a loaf of bread to share." <br />
<br />
"Thank you, but I am full." Orrin said placing a hand to his stomach. <br />
<br />
"Tell me your majesty what has happened to you since you left Donmar?  What of the world and is the Temple as beautiful as the stories tell it to be?" <br />
<br />
Orrin sat by the fire telling Thinopen the tales of what had happened to him.  She sat and listened intently asking questions occasionally as the evening drifted by.  Finally she added more wood to the fire and determined that it was time everyone went to sleep.  Chrystal had already leaned her head against Gingsam and fallen asleep.  Gingsam was about to follow when Thinopen made her announcement.  She insisted that Chrystal slept in her bed and the men were offered quilts for the floor.  Orrin lifted Chrystal and carried her to the woman's bed in the corner and placed her gently under the blankets.  He resisted the urge to kiss her forehead and telling her to sleep well.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
	</td></tr></table>
