	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-06-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">08:01 AM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">13<br />
****<br />
<br />
Morning light seemed to come quickly, rousing them to wake and prepare for the day's travels.  Thinopen offered breakfast, which they ate heartily.  Then she tucked a loaf of bread in a bag for them to take on their journey.   <br />
<br />
As they mounted their horses the birds seemed to sing a happy morning to you song.  Down the twisted mountain path they met few people on the way, and some even recognized Orrin, crying gleefully that their king had returned.  Orrin pleasantly would stop and speak with them.  These were definitely his lands, and he was a kindly king.  <br />
 <br />
The morning melted into a warm afternoon.  The path led them to a covered wooden bridge, before crossing the bridge they walked the horses down to the water’s edge to allow them to drink.  As they stood by the shore a man rode up the path on a horse.  He clopped over the bridge and stopped on the path.  "Are you travelers through or do you have business in this land?" <br />
<br />
Everyone turned to see the speaker.  He was a middle-aged man a bit older than Orrin.  He was well dressed in clothes of perhaps a wealthy merchant or a nobleman.  <br />
<br />
"Squire Mondort!" Orrin exclaimed leaving the horse at the riverbank and heading up to the road where the man sat on his horse. <br />
<br />
The man’s eyes widened and he dismounted from his horse.  "Your Majesty?" Mondort said looking toward his king.  "It is you....  You have returned." Dropped to the grown in a deep kneeling bow.  "I am at your service, whatever you request." He stated as he lifted his head.   <br />
<br />
"You have always been a good man Mondort.  I have returned to get my son from the villain Norlin." <br />
<br />
"What can I do for you sire?" <br />
<br />
Orrin paused a moment to think.  It almost seemed that he had not anticipated this.  Gingsam and Chrystal gathered the horses and brought them over to the road.  "Well..." Orrin began, still in deep thought.  "We have returned to gather an army.  There are others from the outlying areas coming as well to join us.”<br />
<br />
"Sire, then perhaps until we can organize let me invite you to stay at my home.  This will allow you to rest from your long travels." <br />
<br />
"Thank you for such a generous offer." Orrin said with a nod of his head, and he looked over at Chrystal, Gingsam and Godart as they approached.  Godart had hold of both his horse and Orrin’s.  “Might I introduce you to my company.”  He said with a palm out toward the others, “This is Gingsam of Vnalt, and Chrystal Priestess of Yamara, and Godart my page.”  Godart’s ears perked at this new title, and he offered Orrin a huge grin.<br />
<br />
Orrin collected the reins of his horse from Godart and gave the boy a wink.  He mounted his horse the others followed his lead.  Mondort turned his horse around and led the way back over the bridge and along the path he had just come.  They went up the road a little further and turned down a cart path that looked more like a tunnel the way the trees covered it.  At the end of the tunnel the path opened to a grassy meadow on a hill, over looking a small valley with a thin river.  On the side of the crest of a hill stood a modest cottage.  Not a large mansion a squire would usually live in but with everything in Donmar in trying times it was not surprising. <br />
<br />
“My family and I moved out to our summer cottage because of Norlin.”  Mondort explained.  “I hope you don’t mind the accommodations sire.”<br />
<br />
“Anything is better than a nice grassy spot under the stars.”  Orrin returned.  He pulled his horse back slightly to walk next to Chrystal.  "We are close to the castle here." He pointed at a hill beyond the cottage.  "Over that hill you can see the castle.  I will show it to you later if you like." <br />
<br />
"Thank you." Chrystal returned observing the hill he had indicated.  She pondered a moment if they should be so close to the castle with the dragon living there.  What if he swooped in and ate the horses, or decided to burn down the cottage.  Her knowledge of dragons was lacking since it was never her goal to meet one.  She knew Gingsam in his many years had faced a few dragons, perhaps she could talk with him later about what to expect.  For now all she wanted was to be clean, her skin itched with the dirt from their travels.<br />
<br />
Mondort led them to the stable where a young man, most likely his son took the horses to unsaddled and unbridled them.  They let Godart stay with the boy since he now desired to act the part of a royal page.  Leaving the boys at the stable the small group of four went to the cottage.  Since it was still early in the warm afternoon Chrystal decided to mention to Mondort that she desired to bathe.   <br />
<br />
"Of course." He returned, "My wife could probably get you a change of clothes.  Come inside and speak with her.  I'm sure she will have some ideas for you." He offered. <br />
<br />
They walked into the kitchen and on through to a front room, which was filled with light from the large window.  The house faced the east so the mornings had to be bright in this room.  "Rallina!" He called out from the front room.  Shortly feet pattered down the stairs from the upstairs. <br />
<br />
"Mondort?  You have returned early.  I didn't figure you would be home until after dark tonight." She said before she ever made it to the room.  "So what..." She paused when she saw everyone in the room.  When her eyes fell upon Orrin and she fell to her knees.  "Your majesty!  We thought you were dead." She cried looking up at him from the floor. <br />
<br />
"Madam please rise.  I have returned to correct my mistakes and regain our kingdom." <br />
<br />
"We have much to discuss, but the lady here has said she would like to bathe.  Could you help her?" Mondort said cutting in to rescue his wife. <br />
<br />
"Yes, oh yes, Princess how may I help you?" She said bowing before Chrystal. <br />
<br />
"I am not a princess.  I am Chrystal Priestess of Yamara." She said introducing herself. <br />
<br />
Rallina turned her head to the side.  “A Priestess,” She turned to look at Orrin, “We always knew you would return, and with you, you brought a Priestess.  This is a wonderful day indeed.”  She bounced on her toes and clapped her hands together, then tried to calm down her excitement, "Well mi’lady let me see if I can find you a dress and some soap for cleaning." She said as she turned and rushed out of the room.  Shortly she returned, and Chrystal followed her to the river.   <br />
<br />
The water of the river was cold but it felt good in the warm dry afternoon air. Rallina had shown her a nice little area in the river to swim where the trees formed a screen from the cottage.  When she was done and dry, Rallina helped her dress into a white dress with full skirt and a white cloak since evening was approaching.  <br />
<br />
When returned to the cottage Chrystal went into the front room where everyone was sitting, and Orrin was telling the story of his adventures.  He gaped a moment when he saw her.  "You look..." He seemed to search for the correct word. "Nice." <br />
<br />
"Thank you." She blushed and found herself a place to sit and listen.  <br />
<br />
After a time Rallina entered the front room and announced supper was on the table.  Everyone adjourned to the kitchen and sat around the large wooden table that was laden with food from roasted chicken, cheese, and breads, to fruits and green vegetables.  She made sure her king was fed.     <br />
<br />
After the meal Gingsam told everyone he would be sitting in the front room reading.  Chrystal helped Rallina clear the feast and dishes.  <br />
<br />
“You are one of the High Priestesses?”  Rallina asked Chrystal as they cleared the table.<br />
<br />
Chrystal looked down at the dishes she was carrying and smiled.  “No, I’m only a simple Priestess.  My father thought it was best I learn the ways of a healer.”<br />
<br />
“How long?”<br />
<br />
“I’ve been doing so for over a century.”<br />
<br />
She sucked in her breath.  “Your life is extended?”<br />
<br />
“They say it is because of magic that runs through our veins.”<br />
<br />
“I wish I had had a child of magic.”  <br />
<br />
Chrystal set the dishes in the washbasin, and brushed a strand of white hair behind her ear.  She stopped a moment and looked at the small wisp of hair in her fingers.  “Sometimes magic isn’t all you would hope it is.”  Then she put it back behind her ear.<br />
<br />
“I’ll take care of the dishes from here, I don’t know that I like a Priestess doing this sort of work for me.”  Rallina said waving Chrystal off from the work.<br />
<br />
“It is no problem.”  <br />
<br />
“Perhaps I’ll get used to it, but for now off with you.”<br />
<br />
Chrystal respected Rallina’s beliefs and exited the kitchen with a gentle smile.  She made sure to leave the apron hanging on a peg next to the kitchen door.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><i>Last edited by Auroralee on 09-06-2003 at 08:10 AM</i></font></p>
