	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-07-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">10:27 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF"><i>I was finally able to recover the last pages of the story, so it will make it easier to write it.  I dreaded the thought of trying to reconstruct from memory.  To not ruin this part I only have to say that this is the part that one of my friends was telling me he was hoping would be in there somewhere.</i> <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt=""> <br />
<br />
<i>Auroralee Borealis</i><br />
<br />
14<br />
****<br />
<br />
Orrin stood outside the Squire's cottage on the hill over looking the castle.  The light of the full moon flooded the land and made the high stonewalls of the castle gleam white.  A tear ran down his cheek as he looked upon his home.  His family had lived there inside those walls.  Annadell his beautiful wife.  She was an incarnation of beauty and love carefully wrapped up into one woman.  He could almost see her gentle face in front of him.  He so wanted to reach out and hold her.  The more he thought of her the more tears flooded his eyes.  Who said kings don't cry?  He thought to himself as the memories of his wife played in his mind. <br />
<br />
Onjovn.  His eldest son still lived, he just knew it.  Now he needed to focus on him and not Annadell.  Onjovn was all that mattered now.  He dried his eyes of the tears with his hand, and began to study the castle, wondering where Norlin would have hidden the boy. <br />
<br />
"Orrin," Chrystal's soft voice slipped into his thoughts like a refreshing breeze.  "Orrin?"  She said again. <br />
<br />
"Over here."  He answered turning to see her approach.  Her tread was light on the grassy land as she headed up the hill from the cottage.  Her hair blew in the slight breeze and the moonlight illuminated her small face.  The light colored dress she was wearing billowed in the breeze making her look almost like the Goddess of Life herself. <br />
<br />
"I just wanted to make sure you were all right."  She told him when she was almost next him. <br />
<br />
"I'm as well as the circumstances allow."  He told her when she was standing beside him. <br />
<br />
"My!"  She breathed.  "The castle is beautiful." <br />
<br />
"That it is."  They stood quietly for a time watching the castle as the occasional cloud drifted before the moon darkening the walls for a few moments until it passed.  "I grew up there."  Orrin pointed out.  "Now, instead of it being my ancestral home it seems like an unknown place."  Orrin fell silent again, the tears of anger and sadness were threatening to return.   He looked down at Chrystal's little body standing next to him when she mumbled something quietly to herself.  "Cold?"  He asked having come to recognize the spell she was casting on herself. <br />
<br />
"I was."  She confirmed.  Then they fell silent again, until the thought that haunted her every moment returned.  "Orrin…" <br />
<br />
"Yes?" <br />
<br />
"If I'm being followed, by some evil force, why have we not seen it yet?" <br />
<br />
Ah finally a distraction.  "I don't know.  It would certainly make it easier if we knew who or what it was.  Then we would know how to prepare ourselves."  She nodded, her face grew sad.  He was not sure if it was due to the fact that she had been sent away from her people or if it was fear itself.  "When I get my son, we will turn our attention on your pursuer.  Maybe if we hunt it that will give us the chance to avoid being hunted."  <br />
<br />
"We'll find Onjovn."  She said with resolve. <br />
<br />
Orrin reached his arm around her back and placed his hand on her shoulder that was opposite him.  "I'm confident we will." <br />
<br />
The touch of Orrin's hand rather startled her, yet the contact was welcome.  With everything going on lately she needed him, probably as much as he needed her.  As they stood, she thought of the temple and what Nonpree had told her the day she became a student.  She belonged to the Goddess of Life and was not to give herself to anyone else.  She felt guilty because of the thoughts and desires that now flowed through her mind.  Suddenly she concluded that she should not be standing beside him in his arms.  She knew she should step away from him, but the feelings she had for Orrin would not let her. <br />
<br />
"Chrystal." He said softly as he drew her in closer until their bodies touched.  <br />
<br />
"What is it?"  She whispered. <br />
<br />
"Perhaps it is too soon, but I never thought after Annadell died that I would be able to find a friend in another woman.  Until I met you."  He paused then stepped in front of her placing his hands on her shoulders.  "You are a perfect example of the Goddess of Life.  I would almost swear you were she.  You have to be, because you are here as my friend."  <br />
<br />
"With the way things have been, it seems that I need friends."  She told him casting her eyes down as to not look him in the face.  "I have devoted my life to being a Priestess to the Goddess of Life.  To Yamara.  I would never try to claim to be Yamara.  I am here to do her will, as a servant.  It seems that her will is to have me remain by your side, since it is not for me to return to the temple." <br />
<br />
"When you say it in that way it makes me feel guilty for my thoughts."  He told her with an understanding smile. <br />
<br />
"What thoughts?"  She asked, lifting her face to meet his eyes. <br />
<br />
"This," He told her as he leaned his face down to hers and placed his lips on hers.  She leaned into his kiss and he wrapped his arms around her body bringing her closer to him.  <br />
<br />
As they kissed the world around them began to glow red as the moon turned red in the sky.  A wind picked up and dark clouds began to billow and form in the sky.  Soon lightening flashed and thunder rumbled.  Chrystal and Orrin pulled away from each other, and a flash of lightening hit the ground near them blinding them.  It was not a normal flash and where it hit a man stood.  He was a tall man almost as tall as Orrin himself.  He wore long flowing black robes with a cape that billowed and snapped as it blew in the wind.  His long black hair flashed across his face and fluttered behind his head like a banner.  His face was strong and stern, very much like Orrin's and his eyes were a bright blue and seemed to glow from within. <br />
<br />
"Brother," The man said aloud with a sly smile.  "I see that you have returned.  You don't really think you will be reclaiming my kingdom, do you?" <br />
<br />
"It was never your kingdom, Norlin." <br />
<br />
"There you are mistaken again.  It was never yours.  I should have been the one to get Onmil's heritage not you."  Norlin snapped.  "I suggest you leave now and I will spare your life." <br />
<br />
"I'm not leaving until you return my son.  It doesn't matter if I give my own life as long as I can get my son away from you." <br />
<br />
"I will not let you have my son."  Norlin retorted with a maniacal laugh. <br />
<br />
"He is not your son." <br />
<br />
"Everyday he is more mine than he was ever yours."  Then he raised his hands and began to cast a spell.  "Leave now, Orrin!  This in not your home anymore."  With his words he disappeared and rain began to pour down from the black clouds that had covered the moon. <br />
<br />
Released from where they had been standing Orrin and Chrystal grabbed hands and ran for the Squire's cottage.  Gingsam opened the door as they ran at him.  He moved aside from the doorway as the two wet people ran in. <br />
<br />
"Caught in the rain were you?"  Gingsam asked cheerfully when they were all inside. <br />
<br />
"Norlin, started it after leaving."  Orrin grumbled. <br />
<br />
"Norlin?  He was here?" <br />
<br />
“E’s the bad wizard, isn’t ‘e?”  Godart interjected.<br />
<br />
"Yes, he apparently has known of our presence for sometime." <br />
<br />
"All is lost.”  Chrystal added with mourn in her tone.  “We have no element of surprise nor do we have a plan." <br />
<br />
"I have an idea."  Orrin said walking over to the fireplace where the flames danced happily on the wood.  Chrystal joined him to warm herself as well.  "Norlin might have current ownership of the land but he does not have the heart of the people.  Also we have those coming to meet us that the Council promised.  He may have magic on his side, but so do we."  He said glancing at Gingsam.<br />
<br />
"Orrin," Chrystal interrupted.   <br />
<br />
Orrin looked down at her and smiled.  "What is it?" <br />
<br />
"Why did he call you brother?" <br />
<br />
All of his enthusiasm drained from his face as he turned away for a moment to watch the flames dance in the fireplace.  He gave a heavy sigh and began to speak again.  "Before I was born, my father made a grave mistake.  He went outside of his marriage, and a child was born.  That child, Norlin, is my half brother.  He is also older than me by a month." <br />
<br />
"So he has the right to the throne over you?"  Gingsam questioned. <br />
<br />
"I had the first child, and I was given the throne by my father.  Plus, I was the son of the Queen.  Norlin has always rejected that fact and claimed what he believes to be rightfully his.  If he can make others believe Onjovn is his son, then he can claim the throne.  He will turn my son against me, and it will be my child that will kill me.  Effectively making Norlin the rightful heir to the throne of Onmil." <br />
<br />
"Yes, and we need a plan or we are as good as dead."  Squire Mondort said, no one had noticed when he entered the room.  "I always knew there was a reason Norlin came to Donmar.  He is Onmil's mistake.  Onmil was a good man and a wonderful king, too bad he was a bit naive forty years ago.  Anyway young man we need to put you back in your place or the Kingdom of Donmar will be no more." <br />
<br />
"Aye, that we do."  Orrin returned. <br />
<br />
"The hardest part will be that blasted dragon," Gingsam added.  Orrin, Mondort, and Gingsam talked through the night about a plan to return the castle to its rightful heir.  It was going to take men and lots of them.  Men able and willing to stand up to a dragon with their lives.  It was decided that at dawn's early light Orrin, Godart and Mondort would set out in search of these men.  Mondort already had many in mind, plus he knew where much of Orrin's army was hiding.  As the first fringes of light began to streak the sky, the team of three walked out to the small stable to prepare horses for the long ride ahead.  Chrystal quietly followed and Gingsam turned in for some rest, because of a headache.  Silently Chrystal watched as they gathered the two horses all the while lost as to what she should do next.  For a fleeting moment she thought about catching her horse and going with them.    <br />
<br />
"Your Majesty let me prepare your ‘orse."  Godart begged at a nod from Mondort.   <br />
<br />
Orrin understood that Godart wanted to play the part of the proper page and did not protest, but stepped away.  He stood and smiled as they worked to saddle the horses.  Then he turned when he noticed Chrystal near the corral gate.  Stepping away from the working them he stood in front of her placing a gentle hand on her shoulder.  "Come with me."  He told her quietly, as he led the way around to the back of the stable out of view of the cottage, Mondort and Godart.  "I uh, was wondering if…" He stopped moment and searched for his words as thoughts rushed him.  Come with me!  No,no,no!  You are a lady and the riding will be hard.  It is something I don't need you doing.  You will be safe here.  Besides Gingsam is here.  "Please, be careful." He told her aloud.   <br />
<br />
"I will be fine."  She told him with a pleasant assuring smile.  “Gingsam said when he wakes he will try and use his thoughts to search for other armies, and find out how far out they are.” <br />
<br />
"I am confident you will, you are a strong woman."  Then he paused gazing into her dark eyes.  There was more to be said but the words eluded him until only a feeling surfaced above the sea.  "I will miss you."  He said touching her cheek with two fingers, feeling the soft skin as he pushed some of her long white hair out of her face.    <br />
 <br />
She searched his face wanting to remember every detail.  Something screamed in the back of her mind that she could not let him leave.  Would she see him again?  Then she almost asked to come with them.  No!  That was not something she should ask.  "I will miss you."  She finally returned. <br />
<br />
Orrin slipped his fingers into her hair and held the back of her head as he leaned forward and kissed her lips.  When they pulled away a tear ran down Chrystal's cheek and her eyes glittered from extra wetness.   <br />
<br />
"Your majesty?"  Mondort inquired from around the side of the stable.  "Your horse is ready."  They both turned in the direction of the voice to see that Mondort was making sure not to step around the stable.   <br />
<br />
"I'm on my way."  Orrin told him, and then turned to her. "Perhaps I will even be back by this evening."  He assured her as he gently wiped the tear away. <br />
<br />
"I pray of you safe journeys." <br />
<br />
They walked around the stable to find Mondort and Godart mounted atop their horses.  Godart held the reins of Orrin’s horse.  None of them said a word as Orrin quickly leapt atop his saddle.  He gave Chrystal one last smile, and they galloped off down the trail away from the cottage.   <br />
<br />
Once they disappeared she felt very empty and lonely inside.  This was the first time she had truly been parted from Orrin since the day they met in the cave.  The world around her suddenly seemed larger than it had once been.  Looking up at the sky it looked like the same old sky but even that was different.   <br />
<br />
Placing her fingertips to her lips she still felt his kiss.  Why had she kissed him?  It was in direct violation of the laws set before her.  No, she could not fall in love.  Perhaps this was why the Council sent her away.  They must have foreseen this before it actually happened.  This was a test!  They were using this to test her dedication.  Scolding herself for her weakness, she turned toward the cottage.  Orrin could not be the evil that pursued her.  He just could not be she discounted. <br />
<br />
Entering the kitchen she met up with Rallina as she was preparing something.   She hummed a delightful tune as she worked. <br />
<br />
"You have a lovely voice."  Chrystal told her. <br />
<br />
"Why thank you child." Rallina said with a start, but quickly calmed herself  "My goodness you look so tired, perhaps you should go up to the loft room and rest.  Your journeys have probably kept you exhausted and one as lovely as you needs rest." <br />
<br />
"Thank you," She returned not putting up much argument.  She knew she was tired, and needed rest.  She followed the instructions and went into the other room to climb the stairs.  At the top she walked down the slender hall that followed the peak of the roof and found the room she had been offered.  A small room with a large bed in the corner and a window that over looked the river and the valley.  It was not long after she was lying in the bed with the covers pulled up to her neck that she was fast asleep.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
