	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">15<br />
****<br />
<br />
Orrin and his company rode to the different places Mondort led.  Indeed much of his army was still in hiding waiting for the true king to return.  There were tales of the casualties being high and all of the inner kingdom royal guard was killed.  This was not surprising news, but it did raise question in his mind if Onjovn was still alive.  <br />
<br />
“Orrin of no where, we meet again.”  A voice said as a group of travelers appeared out of the trees.  The speaker was a tall slender man dressed in a soft sewn leather suit.<br />
<br />
Raising his hand he halted the now fifty men that followed him.  “Hello,” He knew this slender man from somewhere, but with his present company he could not place why.  They man was joined with a dwarf of a man, a Grot, a gnome caster, and another tall caster like Gingsam.  The Grot had a hand on top of the dwarf’s head and he did not seem to mind.  “We have met.”  He said to them.  <br />
<br />
“That we have, your majesty.”  The first man made a sweeping bow.  “Raymed’s the name, rescuing folks is the game.”  He face beamed as he straightened. <br />
<br />
“Raymed it is a pleasant surprise to see you again.  What brings you to Donmar?”  Orrin nudged his horse to continue forward on the path.  This got the troop to move as well and Raymed’s party kept pace.<br />
<br />
“I heard there was some troubles in Donmar, and that King Orrin son of Onmil was looking for some help.  So I found my favorite friends and said, ‘Remember that healer that brought the breath of life back to Brinog?’  Of course we did.  I said, ‘Well she was traveling with this Orrin fellow, perhaps we can go and help.  And here we are.”<br />
<br />
The rest of his party nodded.  “I owe her my very breath from me lungs.”  Brinog the Grot interjected. <br />
<br />
“Chrystal is with us, and I am certain she will be happy to see all of you when we return to the squire’s cottage.” <br />
<br />
“I never did get to thank her.”  Brinog told him, “Me name is Brinog, and this here is Dromp.”  He said indicating to the dwarf that stayed right at his side.  Brinog was almost as tall as Orrin with a thick tangled beard and a mat of long hair on his head.  His little friend barely stood as high as his knees, but appeared to be a shorter version of Brinog.  <br />
<br />
“Ah yes, and these gentlemen are Hotek, and Holt.”  Raymed said offering the two casters, but not indicating what name went to who.  At the sound of their names they each bowed their heads.<br />
<br />
Orrin also bowed his head to the men.  Two more casters this should make the fight a bit easier.  <br />
<br />
Ahead another group of men appeared on the road, they were dressed for battle, and cheered when they saw Orrin.  More of his army, now if the men the Temple promised would arrive they would stand a strong chance against that dragon.<br />
   <br />
16<br />
****<br />
Her dreams were not easy, they were of battles and blood shed.  She tossed and turned at the clang of metal against metal ringing in her ears.  It was then that the blood began to flow over her bare feet.  She woke when the blood became a river to her knees.   <br />
<br />
The sun was flooding in the window and warming her feet all the way to her knees.  She sighed realizing it was not warm blood on her feet and ankles but warm sunlight.  Sitting up she noticed a simple brown dress that had been laid over the footboard of the bed.  It would better suited for working around the cottage than the white gown she was wearing and the simple dress was much lighter than wearing her heavy leathers.  Again Rallina was tending to her needs.  She stood and dressed in the dress and slipped her feet into a pair of simple cloth shoes, and padded down the stairs.   <br />
<br />
Gingsam sat on a chair reading a leather bound book in the front room near the large window.  "Good afternoon," He said looking up from his reading, "I trust you slept well." <br />
<br />
She decided not to tell him of her troubling dreams, "Yes, the sleep was much needed." <br />
<br />
"Good, good."  He stated still observing her, "Is there something bothering you?" <br />
<br />
"No," Yes, the dream of the battle and the flood of blood, “Were you able to find out about troops?”<br />
<br />
He smiled, “That is good news there are divisions from Cantimor, and Thrusic already at the mountain passes we crossed two days ago.  There are more on the way, but…” He looked down at his book a moment.  “I’m not sure if they will arrive in time.”<br />
<br />
"I wonder how Orrin is doing on his quest to recover his army.  Has he returned?" <br />
<br />
"No, but I'm sure he is doing fine.  He is a very able man, and a good leader.  That is why his men will rally behind him, especially knowing what is at stake." <br />
<br />
"Gingsam," She said a bit more worried, this was probably the real reason for her dream. "Do you think I will be able to care for an army of men?  I mean I have the scepter, but, I don't know what it is capable of, and this could be too much for it." <br />
<br />
"It doesn't seem that Orrin lacks any confidence in you, and to tell you the truth neither do I."  He smiled at her, "This is probably the reason Nonpree gave you the scepter.  It is a powerful item for a Priestess.  Something tells me you won't even have to use it, but that it will work for you."  He shook his head a moment as if to shut out an image.   <br />
<br />
"You saw something.”  She said observing him.<br />
<br />
“I saw nothing.”  He said not wanting to look up at her.<br />
<br />
“What has been foreseen?  I know there is more seen than what is told.” <br />
<br />
"They don't tend to tell the future because it could affect the future.  It is ever changing.  Many outcomes are foreseen.  If they told you it could jeopardize you not taking the right path or giving up." <br />
<br />
"Ahh," She said with final understanding of what he was talking about.  <br />
<br />
He smiled at her briefly before changing the subject again.  "You still worry after Orrin don't you."  He stated. <br />
<br />
"Yes, I do.  It doesn't help my conscience to know that Norlin is aware of us, and what Orrin seeks.  I cannot get over the feeling there is more.  That this almost seems like a trap." <br />
<br />
"He is a powerful man and I'm sure he has also seen the ever changing futures.  He has seen many outcomes to include one where Orrin returns as king, because the people of the valley following him.  He most likely appeared before the two of you to intimidate Orrin.  A flash of his powers and abilities would make most mortal men run in fear.  Last night proved Orrin’s resolve.  We must be on our toes for him to attempt something perhaps a bit more drastic.  This is not a battle we can loose.  This land is not a lone entity in world.  It is a part of the balance of things.  If Norlin takes this land as the true ruler, then it puts everyone in danger.  To include the Temple and my home of Vnalt." <br />
<br />
She took a deep breath, "Then I will do everything in my power."  She said with resolve. <br />
<br />
"I know you will."  He smiled at her again, but the smile did not carry to his eyes. <br />
<br />
Knowing he would not say more, Chrystal turned her thoughts to the growling in her stomach, reminding her it had not seen food for nearly a day.  "I'm going to go see about some food."  She stated, and then turned to the kitchen.  She quickly found some cheese and an apple, then to the pail of water.  It was empty.  The well was just down the hill from the cottage.  She gathered the bucket and her apple, and headed out of the cottage for the well.  The warm day greeted her and the birds chirped happily, they seemed to be trying to remind everyone that evening was only a few hours away. <br />
<br />
She ate her apple as she followed the worn path down the hill to the stone well.  At the well she dropped the bucket attached to a long rope down into the water.  It was a few moments before she heard the bucket plunk into the water.  Then she pulled the much heavier bucket back up. <br />
<br />
"Hello Chrystal."  A man said behind her. Orrin!  <br />
<br />
"Orrin!"  In her excitement she let go of the bucket and turned around ready to throw her arms around his neck.  She stopped when she turned to see that it was not Orrin, but Norlin.  Terror surged through her.   <br />
<br />
"At last I get to meet you."  He said with a smile and a graceful bow. <br />
<br />
Chrystal stepped back and quickly met resistance by the well.  She pushed one of the loose stones off the top into the well and nearly fell in after it.  Quickly she regained her balance.  She had to get away from him.  He stood between her and the cottage.   <br />
<br />
"Don't leave so soon.  I wanted to talk to you."  He told her in a calm voice. <br />
<br />
"I have nothing to say to you."  She returned. <br />
<br />
"But you do."   <br />
<br />
"No, I don't!" <br />
<br />
He smiled, "You bear the mark, therefore we have much to say to one another." <br />
<br />
"What mark?  No one will tell me what the mark is." <br />
<br />
"Why it is the mark of Onmil." <br />
<br />
 "I don't know what you are talking about." <br />
<br />
"When Orrin kissed you the fool inadvertently gave you the mark." <br />
<br />
This puzzled her even more.  What mark could he possibly be speaking of?  "I have had the mark long before he kissed me." <br />
<br />
"No, it is that he kissed you long before you knew it.  He did it in your sleep."  He chuckled. <br />
<br />
"What does the mark mean?"  She could not believe she was standing here talking to him, but he was giving her some of the answers she so sought.   <br />
<br />
"Not fair.  It is my turn." <br />
<br />
"Huh?" <br />
<br />
"I answered something for you now you must do something for me.  Then I will answer more of your questions." <br />
<br />
"Do?"  <br />
<br />
"Knowledge comes at a price, my dear lady."  He said with another sweeping bow.   <br />
<br />
"I need to be going."  She stated. <br />
<br />
"You are not even going to ask what it is I would like?" <br />
<br />
"No."  She told him calculating how to get from the well to the cottage without him knocking her from her feet. <br />
<br />
"Now that is hardly fair.  I gave you something.  I only ask one thing in return." <br />
She swallowed, "What is it?" <br />
<br />
"Thank you, I thought you would never ask.  I only ask that you join me at the castle." <br />
<br />
"Chrystal!"  Gingsam's voice shouted from the direction of the cottage. <br />
<br />
"Help!"  She screamed, and sprinted for the cottage making a wide run around Norlin. <br />
<br />
"You foolish woman."  Norlin said in anger.  "I gave you the chance to come freely." <br />
<br />
Gingsam was running toward her as she ran toward the cottage.  Norlin also turned toward her, but he did not run he only walked in the direction she had taken.  As Chrystal ran for Gingsam he paused a moment to cast an invisibility over her.  She stumbled on a rock and fell to his feet, but she was now out of Norlin's vision. <br />
<br />
"You are Gingsam of Vnalt."  Norlin announced as he approached Gingsam.   <br />
<br />
"Then you know more of me then I of you."  Gingsam retorted. <br />
<br />
"You sit on the High Council at the Temple for Yamara, of course I have heard of you.  I also know enough about you to say that you need to leave.  This is not your battle." <br />
<br />
"I'm sure you have seen what I have seen and know what the out comes are.  You can't win." <br />
<br />
"I can't?  But I already have.  Soon I shall have the only heir to the throne and when he is of age he will rid me of Orrin.  Now if you will step aside I have business to attend to." <br />
<br />
"I believe I am your current business, Norlin."   <br />
<br />
"Oh the mighty Magician wishes to battle a Wizard.  Face the truth boy, you are no match for me.  I will have you drained and dying before you cast your first spell, you don't want to face me." <br />
<br />
"If it deals with Chrystal then it is my business." <br />
<br />
Norlin began to laugh heartily.  "So you think I'm going to harm her?" <br />
<br />
"I don't know what you want her for." <br />
<br />
"I can promise you it is not to harm her.  She is the bearer of the mark.  I could no sooner harm her than myself." <br />
<br />
"So you are the evil that chases her.  Why?"   <br />
<br />
He laughed again.  "That is for me to know, and the future to tell."  He raised a hand to Gingsam, "Now be away with you boy!"  With a flip of his wrist a force hit Gingsam and sent him to the side.  Momentarily stunned Gingsam began to cast a spell, but it was too late Norlin was gone.  He growled at his own absentmindedness to one of the oldest spells.  Gaining his feet he turned himself into a hawk to try to chase down Norlin, or at least help Chrystal. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
While they talked Chrystal scrambled to her feet and ran for the cottage.  When she reached it she found that all the doors were fastened tight.  So she ran for the path that led away from the cottage.  Her feet carried her swiftly as she ran.  She hoped she would run into Orrin on his return to the cottage.  He would know how to stop Norlin from pursuing her.  She reached the main cart road, now she needed to decide left or right.  No time to decide.  Right.  She turned right and ran down the path ahead of her there was a cart on the road.  She ran for it.  Her invisibility spell was also wearing off.  She had to find somewhere to hide now.   <br />
<br />
It was a middle-aged woman walking along side a cart pulled by a weary mule.   <br />
<br />
"Help me!"  Chrystal yelled to the woman as she ran up.  "I need to find Orrin." <br />
<br />
"What do you speak of girl?"  The woman asked, "That is crazy talk everyone knows that King Orrin son of Onmil is dead, and that Norlin is the king now." <br />
<br />
"He is not dead and I need to find him.  I'm being pursued by an evil and I need to get away." <br />
<br />
"I have no way to protect you, be off or I might suffer your fate as well."  The woman hissed and formed a hex sign with her hands. <br />
<br />
Chrystal nearly cried to be shunned by someone in her time of need.  Running further she came to the covered bridge over the river, the same river that ran by the Squires cottage.  There were people on the bridge.  "Help me! Please!"  Chrystal cried out as she made it to the bridge.  "Hide me!" <br />
<br />
It was a small group of three men that looked at her in a queer way.  "What is your fuss woman?"  One of the men demanded.  <br />
<br />
"I am being followed by a horrible wizard."  She said aloud.  She must have been a site covered in dust from running, with a tear-streaked face, wearing a peasant's dress. <br />
<br />
The men laughed at her, "You are a crazy woman."  The speaker announced.  "You are but a servant trying to run from her master.  I have seen your kind too many times.  I won't help you.  We might return you to your master."  The three men began to approach her.   <br />
<br />
Chrystal turned to run as a puff of smoky mist appeared at the far end of the bridge.  It was Norlin.  She quickly turned to her only other option, back the way she had come.  That was when a hawk landed and formed into Gingsam.  Yes, she could run for Gingsam.  He reached for her as she ran to him. <br />
<br />
"Stop!"  Norlin shouted, with his words Chrystal was struck with a force that it knocked her to the ground.  Stunned, she could not stand right away. <br />
<br />
"Gingsam, you still wish to play this game?"  Norlin asked as he stepped further onto the bridge.  The men that had been promising to return her to her master stepped back toward the wall of the bridge.  Fear now filled their once fierce eyes.  "Come now, you know you are no match for me." <br />
<br />
Gingsam, quickly spoke the words to make Chrystal invisible again, but Norlin was faster with a bolt of lightening that flashed from his fingertips making Gingsam loose concentration.  Gingsam reeled backward a step.  He formed a fireball with his hands and with a fierce yell sent it hurtling toward Norlin.  Norlin, deflect the fireball with seemed ease.  Gingsam, was quick to send another.  This time Norlin took the hit.  It knocked him back, but his black robes did not catch fire.  Gingsam sent a third fireball, but it was met by a return of frost from Norlin.  The fireball withered in the air and a snowball fell on the wooden planks of the bridge. <br />
<br />
Finally able to move Chrystal stood and raced toward Gingsam.  At his side she turned on Norlin and called upon the Goddess of Life to help her rain wrath upon Norlin.  The strike from Chrystal must have been unexpected because it knocked Norlin to the ground, for an instant.  This was enough time for her and Gingsam to run. <br />
<br />
They were almost to the turn off to the cottage when Chrystal spotted a troop of men coming up the road.  She pulled on Gingsam and they ran toward the troop.  Norlin appeared before her and collected her in his arms stopping her from joining the army.  He said very little as he cast the spell that made them disappear.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Having seen Chrystal and Gingsam on the path Orrin spurred his horse to meet them when Norlin appeared and stole her.  "No!" He screamed at the man, at the air, at the forest.  Chrystal was gone.   <br />
<br />
Gingsam only stood in place staring at the spot where she last stood.  "He took her.  I couldn't save her.  I failed her.  He took her."  The magician kept repeating his words of disbelief over and over. <br />
<br />
Orrin dismounted his horse and stood before Gingsam.  "What happened?"  He demanded, of the mumbling magician.  "Why are you here, and why did Norlin take Chrystal?" <br />
<br />
"It grows dark Orrin."  Squire Mondort reminded him as he approached.  "We should return to the cottage, my wife will need to help these men, and I'm sure Gingsam needs a moment to collect his thoughts." <br />
<br />
Orrin nodded solemnly and walked silently along side Gingsam back to the cottage leading his horse by the reins.  At the stable Mondort collected the horse while Orrin and Gingsam walked into the cottage.  Gingsam looked very tired and his silk robes were tattered.  Orrin now realized the battle he had led against Norlin was fierce.  Sitting down with Gingsam in the front room of the cottage he waited for the magician to speak. <br />
<br />
"Norlin, is what pursues Chrystal."  Gingsam began.  "I tried to stop him," He explained what he knew of the story to Orrin.  From when he knew to find Chrystal, and that Norlin already stood at the well with her.  He told Orrin of his conversation and of the battle. <br />
<br />
Orrin sat and listened to the whole story and when Gingsam concluded he leaned back in his chair.  "I wonder what the mark is that she bears.  It wasn't that important before now," He paused a moment in thought.  "I believe him when he says he will not harm her but what is she to him?  She is but a Priestess, sure her ability to heal is useful but…" He returned to his inner thoughts for several moments.   <br />
<br />
That was when Rallina entered holding hot cups of tea.  "Mondort thought you might like this."  She offered timidly.   <br />
<br />
"Thank you," Orrin told her as he took the cup from her.  Gingsam offered similar appreciation for his drink, but they remained silent until she had once again left them.  Orrin sipped from his tea and thought.  "I love her."  He finally concluded.  "It is my mark she bears." <br />
<br />
Gingsam was taken back by his words.  "What?  How did you mark her?" <br />
"I don't quite know, but that has to explain why Norlin took such an interest in her.  She and I were brought together, I always assumed by fate but now I don't know.  For all I know she could have always bore the mark but it has just suddenly shown with us finding one another." <br />
<br />
"Hmmm, Interesting.  She is a Priestess.  She cannot love anyone other than her Goddess.  If she does then she can no longer server Yamara." <br />
<br />
"I realize this."  He told Gingsam.  His voice had grown sadder.  "If it were not for that, I think Norlin would have killed her already.  I feared he might go after her before the battle, because she was our chance for success.  But now with what you said about his claim to not harm her that is all I can come up with." <br />
<br />
"We will get her and your son."  Gingsam confirmed. <br />
<br />
There was a knock at the door to the cottage.  Orrin glared at the interruption and Gingsam stood to answer it.  There stood Brinog and Dromp.  They both bowed, “Sire,” Dromp began, “The lady Chrystal came to us in a time of great need, I would like to offer our assistance in finding her for rescue.”  <br />
<br />
“Your being here is certainly going to be a help.”  Gingsam told them.<br />
<br />
Orrin did not want to think right now.  He stood and walked out of the room and up to the bedroom Rallina had prepared for him.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
