</td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-15-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">11:52 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">17<br />
****<br />
Chrystal woke in a room of large cushions and colorful tapestries.  Shaking her head she sat up.  Where was she?  At first glance the room only seemed to have two doors, both most likely locked, but the curtains might also be covering hidden windows.  Near the cushions she had been laid was a short table.  A top the table a large silver goblet sat next to a tray of crackers, cheese, grapes, and plums.  Scooting closer to the table she could also smell the rich smells and her stomach reminded her of its hunger.  No, she must not touch the food, it could be enchanted. <br />
<br />
A door opened and a young woman entered.  She was dressed in a simple gray dress, and her sleek black hair was pulled back into a long braid that fell down her back to well below her waist.  In her hands she carried a washbasin.  "Your majesty.  Would you care to wash up?" <br />
<br />
"Where am I?" <br />
<br />
"You are home."  The girl replied in surprise.  "But your majesty if I might say we must get you into something cleaner and wash you.  Your knees and hands are scraped as if you had been working, and that is hardly how a queen should present herself before the court." <br />
<br />
"Queen?" <br />
<br />
"Yes, you majesty." <br />
<br />
"What do you speak of dear?" <br />
<br />
"You are the Queen of Donmar, after all you bare the mark." <br />
<br />
Chrystal sat full upright, and climbed out of the cushions to put her feet on solid flooring.  "How do I get out of here?" <br />
<br />
The girl only gave her a curious look, but did not answer. <br />
<br />
"You say you are in my service and that I'm your queen and yet you do not answer my questions.  You know more serve me than a horse, and I think that would service me better.  Be off with you."   <br />
<br />
The young woman stood very still and only stared at Chrystal.  The water in her hands shook a bit, either from the weight or from fear of Chrystal beating her.  After a time she spoke in a whisper, "His majesty said that I must do this or he will beat me.  I can tell you no more than I have." <br />
<br />
Looking at the girl Chrystal took pity on her.  She knew that Norlin could be a very brutal man, and she could only assume that was of whom the girl spoke.  "I understand."  Her voice had taken a softer tone.  "I will wash, but I would like to do it alone, and I would rather do it in a bath house." <br />
<br />
"I could ask if you can be taken to the baths.  I don't know if his majesty will allow for it.  He has already stated you are not to run freely through the castle, and I would be very honored if you allowed me to wash your hair." <br />
<br />
Chrystal smiled at her, "All right."  She consented.<br />
<br />
"Oh thank you, your majesty.  I have never seen hair as white as yours." <br />
<br />
"Thank you, but it was more of an accident when I was younger.  My hair used to be black very much like your own.  I was but a child when I got into my father's spell book.  I thought I would surprise him with a spell that I was sure I could learn.  Either I said or did something wrong and there was an explosion, when I woke to my father rocking me in his arms he scolded me for the use of his spell book and decided that that was when I needed to start my apprenticeship.  The following day he took me before the High Priest to ask for an apprenticeship.  I didn't know that my hair had turned pure white right away, it was that night when I went to brush it out.  I ran screaming to my father to have him change it back.  He refused and I have had white hair ever since." <br />
<br />
"At least you didn't turn yourself into a toad." <br />
<br />
Chrystal laughed at this.  "You are right."  Then she paused and looked at the dark haired girl.  "What is your name?" <br />
<br />
"Sonale, your majesty." <br />
<br />
"You don't have to call me your majesty." <br />
<br />
The young girl smiled.  She began her work of preparing the water in her bowl to wash Chrystal.  "There is a gown over there for when we have you cleaned." <br />
<br />
Chrystal frowned at the gown, it was beautiful with yards of material, but it would make it hard run if she needed to. <br />
<br />
"I hope it is to your liking. Please, lay here."  She indicated to a cushion, and then she placed her bowl of water near it and towel next to it. <br />
<br />
"It's very lovely."  Chrystal said as she lied down with Sonale's help.  Soon Sonale was using a pitcher to wet Chrystal's hair, and scrubbing a lovely smelling soap into it.   <br />
<br />
"It used to belong to Annadell," Sonale explained as she worked.  "She was a very lovely woman like yourself.  If it doesn't fit properly I was told to make it tailor fit you.  Tomorrow the castle tailors will come and measure you for your own dresses." <br />
<br />
"What do you know of the queen Annadell?" <br />
<br />
"Oh she was a lovely woman.  Tall and slender with hair of red like the setting sun, and she was as kind as a mountain doe.  I don't think I ever heard her raise her voice, not to anyone.  Then Norlin came,” Her voice trailed off and her hands stopped moving.  After a moment she seemed to realize what she was doing.  "Anyway, you are the queen now.  I just hope Orrin can save you before Norlin takes you as a bride."   <br />
<br />
"What?" <br />
<br />
"I don't really know more than that.  I just know that Norlin plans to kill Orrin with the prince." <br />
<br />
"Is Onjovn here at the castle?" <br />
<br />
"I don't know, this is my tower of the castle.  If he's here he would be in another tower, but I didn't know that any of the children lived.  When Norlin came he only spared some of the servants lives and I was one of them, otherwise everyone else was burned by the dragon Ictom, or slain by his hideous army of creatures." <br />
<br />
The girl continued to work on Chrystal's hair scrubbing it, then rinsing it, and finally drying it.  Chrystal's thoughts were elsewhere.  She needed to find Onjovn, and let him know that his father was coming for him, and then she would need to figure a way to help with the battle.  The men would need her.  Gingsam's words hung heavy in her mind.   <br />
<br />
"What did you say?"  Sonale asked. <br />
<br />
Chrystal did not realize she had spoken out loud.  "Nothing."   <br />
<br />
Sonale helped Chrystal finish washing and helped her into Annadell's dress.  It was breathtaking the lace had to be spun gold.  The flowing material fit her as if it were made for her.  Sonale hung a large gold necklace around Chrystal's neck and finally placed a gold crown upon her head.   <br />
<br />
"Come see yourself in the looking glass."  She said excitedly when her work was done. <br />
<br />
Chrystal followed and looked at herself in the indicated looking glass.  At first she could not believe who she was looking at.  It was not the Chrystal she had always seen in past looking glasses.  This time she radiated beauty.  The gold crown upon her head glowed in her white hair, and the dress was that of a queen.  "I,I can't dress like this."  Chrystal stammered.  "I'm a Priestess." <br />
<br />
"You are?"  Sonale asked in astonishment.  "I didn't know you were a Priestess." <br />
<br />
"This is far above my station."  She knew she could not dress above her station.  "I'm not a queen." <br />
<br />
There was a tap at the door, and a moment later the door opened.  Both Sonale and Chrystal turned to see Norlin step in.  He was no longer dressed in black robes but in a suit of black with tall black boots.  He paused a moment at the door as he looked at Chrystal.  The look of astonishment flashed across his face but he quickly hid it with a smile.  "Good evening Chrystal.  I was coming to ask if you are ready to dine with me.  From the look of things you are." <br />
<br />
"I won't be dining with you."  Chrystal said sternly. <br />
<br />
"You will."  He returned and bowed.  When he straightened he walked toward her and collected her hand.  "You are beauty itself." <br />
<br />
She pulled her hand away quickly.  "I won't go anywhere with you." <br />
<br />
"Oh?" <br />
<br />
"I would rather starve here then go anywhere with you." <br />
<br />
"Now Chrystal you would not want to see the servant girl get whipped because you will not join me for dinner."  He said with a hiss pointing a hand at Sonale.  Terror flashed across the young woman's face. <br />
<br />
Chrystal swallowed hard.  She would be able to heal the poor girl's wounds, but she did not want to see the young thing go through it.  "No I would not."  She submitted, looking toward the floor and not at either of them.   <br />
<br />
"Then it is settled, come now my dear."  He said gathering her hand again.  This time she did not pull away but walked by his side.  Through the door they walked down winding stairs that ended at a great hall.  It was a hall of marble floors and granite walls laden with gold and silver.  Portraits in huge gold frames hung on the walls and grand candle chandeliers of crystal dangled from the ceiling.  They continued through the hall to a pair of wooden doors.  Norlin raised a hand to the doors and they obediently opened.  He continued to lead her through the doors to a large banquet hall.  There were only two seats prepared at one end of the long table.  He walked her to a chair next to the head of the table, the chair pulled away from the table on its own and he helped her sit.  Then the chair returned her to the table.  He did the same with the chair at the head of the table and sat.   <br />
<br />
Chrystal did not feel much like eating anymore even though the food in front of her smelled wonderful.  She poked a golden fork into it and tried to eat.  She knew to be any use to Orrin she must still keep her strength up. <br />
<br />
<br />
Norlin paused often in his eating to look at her.  "I do have to say this of Orrin, he always had good taste in women."  He told her. <br />
<br />
"Now that I'm here tell me about the boy." <br />
<br />
"Boy?" <br />
<br />
"Yes Onjovn first son of Orrin." <br />
<br />
"There is no one in the castle of that name anymore." <br />
<br />
"You said you had him here and were turning him." <br />
<br />
"Onjovn died along side his mother I could not keep any of Orrin's children alive, they would be heirs to the throne.  Though if this Onjovn was the eldest of his sons I must say he was a gallant young fellow.  He stood up tall to me before he died with his sword drawn."  He told her with almost pride in his voice. <br />
<br />
Chrystal's heart sank at this dreadful news.  "Then all this talk of the eldest prince living is all a trap?" <br />
<br />
"No." <br />
<br />
More riddles to figure out.  What was it he knew? <br />
<br />
"The prince has not been born yet, the queen has yet to marry the king.  Then the prince that is born to them shall rule all of Donmar.  The queen is the woman that bears the mark of Onmil.  Does that answer your question?" <br />
<br />
"My question?"  She paused a moment, "So the mark says I will be the queen, but I'm not going to marry." <br />
<br />
"Yes you are." <br />
<br />
"I'm a Priestess, I am not to marry." <br />
<br />
"You are in love with Orrin?" <br />
<br />
"No." <br />
<br />
"Since you are in love with him, you will marry me." <br />
<br />
"No." <br />
<br />
Norlin leaned back in his chair and laughed.  "You don't understand do you?  You are the queen of Donmar and I am the king.  We shall be married in three days and by next year you will have given me a son." <br />
<br />
"Why would I do such a thing?  If I say no will you kill me instead?"<br />
 <br />
"You don't value your life enough.  As a Priestess you would rather die than see another hurt in your place.  So I shall tell you this once.  If you refuse, you have sent Orrin to a torturous death, one I would be sure you watched and were not able to help him.  Thus, you can do as I say or watch him die." <br />
<br />
Chrystal looked down at her plate and the uneaten food.  The thought of Orrin suffering because of her was not what she was here for.  She was here to save lives especially his.  Tears filled her eyes.  "If I consent do you promise not to hurt him?" <br />
A smiled tugged at the corners of his mouth.  "I will not harm him."<br />
 <br />
"Then I will marry you." A lump formed in her throat at the thought of marrying him.  Then the only hope she could think of was taking her life before the wedding or soon after.  She could not give him the son he desired.   <br />
<br />
"My mother said you were a good woman." <br />
<br />
"How does your mother know of me?" <br />
<br />
"She met you." Norlin said with a grin, "Do you remember the widow, Madam Thinopen?" <br />
<br />
"She is your mother?"  <br />
<br />
"Of course, she was never the queen, but unlike the queen before Annadell she is still alive."  <br />
<br />
Chrystal's head was beginning to swim, and ache.  She put her hand on her forehead.  "I want to go rest my head." She felt as though she had just made a deal with the king of the dead.  How could she have done this?  Was she that in love with Orrin that she would give herself to this evil man in the hopes that Orrin would live? <br />
<br />
"Sonale, take the queen to her quarters." He ordered with a wave of his hand. <br />
Soon Sonale was by her side and walking her back to the tower.  Then she undressed her, laid her on a bed and tucked covered her with a blanket.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
