</td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 09-16-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">12:02 AM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">18<br />
****<br />
<br />
Orrin sat bolt upright in the darkness of his room.  He was still in his clothes, because he was so exhausted and torn by the loss of Chrystal that he had cried himself to sleep.  He was certain a voice had spoken to him.  Not sure if it was there or not he sat and listened.  There was not a sound in the room, it must have been a dream.  He lied back down on the bed.   <br />
<br />
"Orrin!" The sound was faint but it was there.  Sitting up he threw his feet over the side of the bed and looked around the room. <br />
<br />
"Orrin of Donmar son of Onmil, your troops must be ready by tomorrow afternoon or her life will be lost." <br />
<br />
"Who's there?" Orrin asked. <br />
<br />
The voice was neither male nor female, but it was one he had heard before.  "The power that pursued Chrystal has her and grows stronger each day...  If you fail everything will be lost." The voice was fading in and out.  It seemed to be struggling against something. <br />
<br />
"Who are you?" <br />
<br />
"The Oracle, which you lost.  I can't stay..." The voiced faded again.  "He has push......out of your realm...Save the queen and you will take your kingdom..." <br />
<br />
"Annadell is dead." He said in surprise. <br />
<br />
"Annadell is dead, but the queen isn't...I can not stay."  <br />
<br />
"Is Chrystal the queen?" Orrin asked.  There was no reply.  "Oracle?" Still silence.  The oracle was no longer with him.  He sat for a long time listening for the Oracle's return until his eyelids grew heavy. <br />
<br />
The morning sun seemed come quick waking Orrin, but he did not forget the Oracle’s words.  Finding Gingsam, he told him of his meeting with the Oracle.  "We can no longer wait, the time has come.”  Gingsam returned with a frown. “I only wish we had more time to wait for the other two divisions on the way."  <br />
<br />
Orrin turned to Godart who stood silently behind him.  “I have an idea, would you find me Brinog, Dromp, and Holt.”  He instructed the boy.<br />
<br />
“Yes sir.”  He said with a quick bow and ran out the door.<br />
<br />
"I will gather the Officers." Mondort also told him with a bow replying to the unasked question. <br />
<br />
"Thank you." Orrin told the man as he made haste for the door.  "I hope Chrystal is all right." Orrin told Gingsam once they were alone. <br />
<br />
Gingsam paused for a moment as if trying to sense something far away.  "She is for now." He paused again and smiled.  "She is sleeping." <br />
<br />
Orrin's heart ached for her, but it relaxed slightly as he thought of her resting, and he extended his thoughts wishing he could do what Gingsam could do and actually see her.  "I have a plan that ought to save both her and my son." Orrin told him.   <br />
<br />
"Tell me." <br />
<br />
"Norlin will be expecting the battle to carry on out side the castle gates probably assuming his dragon and his army will easily defeat us.  I will have the men draw his army in front of the dragon and they will mix making it harder for Norlin to direct the dragon.  While this is happening you and I go through the side entrance to the castle, it will be easy since you can turn us invisible.  That is where Brinog, Dromp and Holt come in.  They will be decoys looking like us." <br />
<br />
Gingsam nodded.   <br />
<br />
"Once inside we can find Chrystal and Onjovn.  I can almost imagine where he has been keeping them.  Then once we have them safe and free of the castle we pull back and save the battle for another day when the other divisions are arrived." <br />
<br />
"The plan would work, but what is to stop him from returning and taking her as he did this time?  I'm capable of many things, but to keep her from him, will be nearly impossible.  Second, I am worry after Onjovn.  I don't know that he is alive and fear searching for him would take too long.  I cannot seem to locate any of your children in the castle.  I have been trying since we arrived.  I also have to remember Norlin is powerful in the craft and could hide the boy from my reach." <br />
<br />
Orrin took a deep breath, "So my son is dead?" <br />
<br />
"I think so.  I have a feeling that all of this was an elaborate trap for Chrystal.  I don't know why but it seems she is a very critical part of all of this." <br />
<br />
Orrin shook his head in disbelief.  "But I thought you could see if someone was lying?  It is what you are best known for!  Everyone has mentioned my son."  <br />
<br />
Gingsam stood quiet for a time, he closed his eyes mumbled some words and his pipe appeared in his hand ready to smoke.  He then opened his eyes and chewed on the mouthpiece.  "No one has lied about the prince not even the old crone on the mountain, but never did they put the boy's name with the prince.  I don't know that the prince has been born yet." He chewed some more on his pipe before speaking again.  "The crone spoke of Norlin in such a fine light that I worried she was a spy for him, yet I could not find that she was lying only not telling the whole truth." <br />
<br />
Orrin felt every crumb of his energy crumbling away like a dried out flower that was finally crushed.  He collapsed to his knees.  "She has betrayed me, and I put Chrystal in danger." He knew now that he could no longer continue and that he had wronged everyone for selfish reasons.<br />
<br />
“Orrin pull your wit about you!”  Gingsam demanded.  “I know you would never harm Chrystal not even if it meant she was going to harm you.”  He reached down a hand to place under Orrin’s arm.  “The Godart and Squire Mondort should return soon and you need to tell everyone the plan.  No matter what we need to save her and bring your kingdom back to you the true king named by Onmil himself.”  He gently helped Orrin stand to his feet.<br />
<br />
Orrin stood to his full height and tried to regain some of his strength back to his face as the door burst open with first Godart and five men it seemed they were an inseparable bunch.  Mondort was quick on his heels with the three officers in tow.  <br />
<br />
“Come in and sit.”  Orrin told the men as they bowed before him.  Once they were seated he told them of his plan to enter the castle as the men kept the dragon, Norlin, and the army occupied.  He knew if the dragon was controlled by Norlin’s thoughts that he would need to be nearby leaving the castle unguarded.<br />
<br />
“I know that my men are ready, your majesty.”  One of the officers told him.<br />
“Thank you, Sir Henor.”  Orrin returned to him.  “We also have to begin before the sun reaches the highest point of the day so I shall waste time no more with talk and let you gather your men.”<br />
<br />
“You think I can look like you?”  Brinog said in surprise.  “T’be an honor to be you.”<br />
<br />
“I’ll see to it that he is trimmed and dressed for his kingly duties, your majesty.”  Dromp said bowing. <br />
<br />
Orrin put a hand on Dromp’s shoulder as he turned to leave, “Can he ride?”<br />
<br />
“Yes yer majesty.”  Brinog returned, “I get to ride your horse too?”  He sounded like a child about to be given a gift.<br />
<br />
Orrin nodded and they exited to prepare for the battle.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Noon came and they began the march on the castle gates.  Brinog dressed as Orrin led the way toward the castle with Holt at his side acting as Gingsam.  Orrin and Gingsam kept pace with the army to the castle. They did want not to stray far for fear of raising Norlin’s suspicion that they were trying to save Chrystal.  <br />
<br />
As promised the castle gates were closed but an army of monsters stood waiting outside the walls for Orrin’s small army.  The dragon, Ictom, stood ready in the middle of Norlin’s army.  He was an impressive beast standing tall enough it seemed his head would touch the sky.  He stood on four powerful clawed feet all bigger than a horse.  On his gray scaly back were huge wings tucked back as he stood.<br />
<br />
Orrin had never slain a dragon but knew this would not be easy since they were magical creatures.  Nor had he seen an army of such ugly creatures, he hoped they would be easier than that huge monster.  He looked to Brinog and the officers and they nodded to him, encouraging their men.  Stepping away from the others Orrin and Gingsam disappeared.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
